<xmi:XMI xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1">
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DeliveryProcessDescription xmi:id="-TES1qTtCrxuX-BlE3VOaDg" name="ea_enterprise_architecture,_M6m4MchNEdyU89e0dKAsrw" guid="-TES1qTtCrxuX-BlE3VOaDg">
    <mainDescription>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_UAM__delivery_process&quot; name=&quot;XE_UAM__delivery_process&quot;>&lt;/a> &#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    This process delivers the combined tasks, techniques, and guidance from the Unified Architecture Method (UAM), but&#xD;
    integrated with and augmented through reference to other supporting material. The delivery process is intended to focus&#xD;
    the reader only on those aspects core to&amp;nbsp;UAM architecture definition, and while there may be additional useful&#xD;
    techniques referred to within the methodology, the delivery process brings to the fore the necessary critical elements.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The phases described in this delivery process are intended to be iterative in themselves as well as an assumption that&#xD;
    multiple instances of these processes may be underway with the enterprise. For example, given a complete set of&#xD;
    artifacts from the Business&amp;nbsp;Perspective phase, multiple&amp;nbsp;Logical Perspective&amp;nbsp;phases may be executed to&#xD;
    divide up the architecture effort, likely along business lines, business&amp;nbsp;domains, or projects.&amp;nbsp;Each IT&#xD;
    architecture project will be responsible for progressing a subset of the EA level architecture.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>IT architecture is mandatory in any organization with more than about 100 employees, or even less. System&#xD;
and&amp;nbsp;processes and people are all interconnected, through networks and other ways, in order to support the goals of the&#xD;
enterprise. This &lt;em>connectivity&lt;/em> cannot be understood, optimized, implemented and managed properly without the&#xD;
creation of abstract models. These models support the decision making required to evolve the enterprise's information&#xD;
technology that it turn supports the goals of the organization.</usageGuidance>
    <purpose>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_Delivery__Overview&quot; name=&quot;XE_Delivery__Overview&quot;>&lt;/a> &#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The purpose of this reference process is to provide the activities and tasks for following the Unified Architecture&#xD;
    Method. This reference process defines many parallel processes and activities, but provides structure where required,&#xD;
    including reviews and milestones.&#xD;
&lt;/p></purpose>
    <howtoStaff>&lt;p>&#xD;
    As illustrated in&amp;nbsp;&lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../UAM/guidances/roadmaps/uam_ad_governance_D3C747FE.html&quot; guid=&quot;_0TknkGjpEeS7ieerwXbTqg&quot;>Roadmap: AD&#xD;
    Governance&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;it is recommended that the enterprise have a single Enterprise (Chief IT) Architect plus a Business&#xD;
    Line (Domain) Architect for each business line. Enterprise-wide standards and guidance will be provided and managed by&#xD;
    the Enterprise Architect, while the Domain (Business Line) Architects do the same for their portion of the enterprise.&#xD;
    It is likely that IT architectural issues are quite different in each business line,&amp;nbsp;but this will&#xD;
    be&amp;nbsp;dependent upon the size and type of business. This architectural governance structure also has clear spans of&#xD;
    control, with enterprise-wide issue being the responsibility of the Enterprise Architect. A typical, reasonably sized&#xD;
    enterprise, will therefore likely have:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Enterprise Architect&lt;/strong> - responsible for the overall enterprise IT structure and standards;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Corporate Domain Architect&lt;/strong> - responsible for the network infrastructure, common services (e.g.,&#xD;
        email, web, etc.), and corporate applications (e.g., HR systems, Financial COTS systems, etc.);&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Business Line Architect&lt;/strong> - responsible for the architecture of business-line specific systems.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>Thus, there are typically two basic architects (i.e., Enterprise and Corporate), plus an IT architect for each&#xD;
business line if the size of the enterprise warrants it.&lt;br /></howtoStaff>
    <scope>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_Delivery__Overview&quot; name=&quot;XE_Delivery__Overview&quot;>&lt;/a> &#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    IT Architecture sometimes drives, or is driven by, the need for transformation within the business. But more often, it&#xD;
    is done to clarify the long-term (strategic) goals of the enterprise as reflected by and supported by information&#xD;
    technology. The architecture process may be focused on one of the following:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Transformation of the business (i.e., Business Process Reengineering) captured in an IT architecture;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Consolidation of IT (information technology) services into a normalized set;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Addition of new capabilities to an existing business process;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Definition of new business process(es);&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Definition of a new IT environment in support of strategic business goals;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Definition of enterprise or business domain architectural IT standards.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    This list is by no means complete. There are many reasons for doing IT architecture. The techniques here may also be&#xD;
    applied to all aspects of the enterprise IT, including those that support IT requirements (e.g., network monitoring and&#xD;
    management functions for example).&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;/p></scope>
    <usageNotes>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The delivery process allows for many parallel activities, since there may be multiple strategies&amp;nbsp;underway,&#xD;
    and&amp;nbsp;multiple enterprise or business domain level projects underway. Also, Architectural Decisions may arise at&#xD;
    anytime and anywhere within the enterprise. A separate governance process has been defined for Architectural Decisions:&#xD;
    &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/guidances/roadmaps/uam_ad_governance_D3C747FE.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_0TknkGjpEeS7ieerwXbTqg&quot;>Roadmap: AD Governance&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    UAM has governance processes incorporated into its Delivery Processes, including architectural assessments, and&#xD;
    milestone reviews. See: &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../UAM/deliveryprocesses/uam_it_architecture_del_8B27C350.html&quot; guid=&quot;_M6m4MchNEdyU89e0dKAsrw&quot;>Delivery&#xD;
    Process: IT Architecture Delivery&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    However, each enterprise has its own governance processes for the business and associated IT systems. A separate&#xD;
    generic governance process has been defined within UAM that specifies where and how to integrate UAM within these&#xD;
    pre-existing enterprise processes. See:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../UAM/deliveryprocesses/uam_it_architecture_in-ent_4608CDE7.html&quot; guid=&quot;_YHA_kafREeS8vLSVufajPQ&quot;>Delivery&#xD;
    Process: UAM in the Enterprise&lt;/a>&#xD;
&lt;/p></usageNotes>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DeliveryProcessDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription xmi:id="-n31CYOvDpZ6r-ooNuWk8gg" name="ea_architectural_decision,_wP64kMhQEdyU89e0dKAsrw" guid="-n31CYOvDpZ6r-ooNuWk8gg">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;span lang=&quot;EN-US&quot;>This phase has the following goals:&lt;/span>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Create an Architecture Decision (AD): &#xD;
        &lt;ul>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Define the context of the problem, issue or decision;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Define the constraints, imposed by existing architecture, enterprise standards or others;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Define the rationale for the decision, through a well researched summary of the facts;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Extract the implications of the AD, on current systems, future systems, support aspects and other aspects;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Define or refine the specifics of the decision;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
        &lt;/ul>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Get the AD reviewed and approved by the appropriate review body;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Update the Architecture Glossary as required.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>&lt;span&#xD;
style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Times New Roman','serif'; mso-fareast-font-family: 'Times New Roman'; mso-ansi-language: EN-CA; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA&quot;>&lt;font&#xD;
 face=&quot;Arial&quot;>An architectural decision may be defined at any time during the development of an architecture, a project,&#xD;
during business planning and in many other situations. This is an on-going activity.&lt;/font>&lt;/span></usageGuidance>
    <purpose>The purpose of this activity is to define an Architectural Decision and get it approved and published. Documenting&#xD;
important decisions provides a repository (of decisions) that will help guide other architects, managers, and implementers&#xD;
in being compliant with enterprise and business domain standards. They also provide a source of information for re-visiting&#xD;
decisions over time.</purpose>
    <howtoStaff>&lt;span&#xD;
style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Times New Roman','serif'; mso-ansi-language: EN-CA; mso-fareast-font-family: 'Times New Roman'; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA&quot;>&lt;font&#xD;
 face=&quot;Arial&quot;>This activity is best carried out by an individual or a small team (playing the role of Architect), and&#xD;
usually guided by one or two individuals who have deep experience in architecting systems in the relevant domain. It is&#xD;
composed or staffed&amp;nbsp;with cross-functional team members. Issues that are typically architecturally important include&#xD;
structure, technology, performance, scaling, distribution, or other specialty engineering requirements. Significant&#xD;
architectural constraints might also flow from physical and environmental requirements.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font>&lt;/span></howtoStaff>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-HAUiDa4_KZ4LAA9cpTP2IQ" name="ea_review_AD_management,_PnzIIchWEdyU89e0dKAsrw" guid="-HAUiDa4_KZ4LAA9cpTP2IQ"/>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-iCpkJi76w1blNVXMO0R2Dw" name="New Task Descriptor_5,_2QjeENpTEdyp3veHciZnuA" guid="-iCpkJi76w1blNVXMO0R2Dw">
    <keyConsiderations>This approach should only be followed if there is real urgency, since many valuable steps are skipped or analysis is&#xD;
limited&amp;nbsp;and therefore detail will be missing from the final result. It's a question of balancing the risk of not&#xD;
completing the architecture in time versus leaving out important analysis that may come back to cause problems down the&#xD;
road.</keyConsiderations>
    <usageGuidance>&lt;p>&#xD;
    This&amp;nbsp;activity focuses on&amp;nbsp;the&amp;nbsp;delivery of simple Logical level views of the architecture.&#xD;
    It&amp;nbsp;simplifies the documentation required on the architecture, namely fewer models and simpler models.&#xD;
&lt;/p></usageGuidance>
    <refinedDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    This simplified approach to producing an architecture does not come without a cost. Important analysis is not done, and&#xD;
    therefore detail will be missing or aspects not examined properly.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    This approach is faster because it leverages existing information such as:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Documentation on existing systems;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Documentation on existing architectures;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Documented and relevant architectural decisions;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Enterprise or industry architectural patterns.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    This approach simplifies the documentation required for the architecture, namely fewer models and simpler models. The&#xD;
    &quot;simple&quot; IT architecture is typically focused on one or two aspects; &lt;em>Location&lt;/em> for example, to re-architect the&#xD;
    IP network.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;em>&lt;strong>Note&lt;/strong>&lt;/em>: Simple models are only defined at the Logical or Technical level since existing&#xD;
    documentation may not include the business level, and the focus is at the Logical or Technical levels due to the&#xD;
    urgency and time constraints placed on the project.&#xD;
&lt;/p></refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-5SxaSF067K3XXdBmhFPytw" name="New Task Descriptor_7,_DM1HQdpUEdyp3veHciZnuA" guid="-5SxaSF067K3XXdBmhFPytw">
    <keyConsiderations>This approach should only be followed if there is real urgency, since many valuable steps are skipped or analysis is&#xD;
limited&amp;nbsp;and therefore detail will be missing from the final result. It's a question of balancing the risk of not&#xD;
completing the architecture in time versus leaving out important analysis that may come back to cause problems down the&#xD;
road.</keyConsiderations>
    <usageGuidance>&lt;p>&#xD;
    This&amp;nbsp;activity focuses on&amp;nbsp;the&amp;nbsp;delivery of simple Technical level views of the architecture.&#xD;
    It&amp;nbsp;simplifies the documentation required on the architecture, namely fewer models and simpler models.&#xD;
&lt;/p></usageGuidance>
    <refinedDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    This simplified approach to producing an architecture does not come without a cost. Important analysis is not done, and&#xD;
    therefore detail will be missing or aspects not examined properly.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    This approach is faster because it leverages existing information such as:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Documentation on existing systems;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Documentation on existing architectures;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Documented and relevant architectural decisions;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Enterprise or industry architectural patterns.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    This approach simplifies the documentation required for the architecture, namely fewer models and simpler models. The&#xD;
    &quot;simple&quot; IT architecture is typically focused on one or two aspects; &lt;em>Location&lt;/em> for example, to re-architect the&#xD;
    IP network.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;em>&lt;strong>Note&lt;/strong>&lt;/em>: Simple models are only defined at the Logical or Technical level since existing&#xD;
    documentation may not include the business level, and the focus is at the Logical or Technical levels due to the&#xD;
    urgency and time constraints placed on the project.&#xD;
&lt;/p></refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription xmi:id="-6Jy8F6td__mWbtzo9z3mRg" name="ea_simple,_mXwvgNpKEdyp3veHciZnuA" guid="-6Jy8F6td__mWbtzo9z3mRg">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The architectural review done in&amp;nbsp;this context involves ensuring that the architecture addresses the objectives of&#xD;
    the IT architecture project, and that it fits in with the enterprise direction in the long-term. Scenarios may be used&#xD;
    to test the architecture. If there is a problem in the direction taken by the architecture in terms of the enterprise&#xD;
    long-term objectives then management will need to be made aware of and bless this deviation in direction.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Evaluation Criteria:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Existing architectures have been reviewed and summarized.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/workproducts/uam_arch_context-objectives_874E760A.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_tjC3QMOdEdyILM4NThxMFg&quot;>Context and Objectives&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;has been defined and met.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Agreement on defined Architectural Decisions has been reached.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The Simple Models have been defined and agreed.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Main Artifacts:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Simple Architecture Models&lt;/strong>&amp;nbsp;- completed;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Architecture Decisions&lt;/strong> - stable and agreed by all stakeholders;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Business Glossary&lt;/strong> -&amp;nbsp;refined.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>Typically a &quot;stakeholder review&quot; is done once this peer review has been completed. See: &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
href=&quot;./../../UAM/deliveryprocesses/uam_architecture_review_524E0258.html&quot; guid=&quot;_aBL6oMhSEdyU89e0dKAsrw&quot;>Phase: Review the&#xD;
Architecture&lt;/a>.</mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>This review milestone is&amp;nbsp;a formal&amp;nbsp;&lt;em>peer review&lt;/em> where&amp;nbsp;the IT architecture is reviewed by IT experts,&#xD;
other participants, and peers to ensure that it is complete, consistent, and meets objectives.&amp;nbsp;</usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-IwPoug8-Bs0sjViA_1aibw" name="ea_analyse_existing,_xtT8kNp4EdyFbt-dvvmLCA" guid="-IwPoug8-Bs0sjViA_1aibw">
    <usageGuidance>In the context of documenting an existing architecture, leveraging existing work and information is the way to go. Not only&#xD;
are architectural decisions a good source of information, existing project and system documentation is invaluable.</usageGuidance>
    <refinedDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Existing Architecture Analysis is the process of leveraging existing architectural assets (e.g. existing architecture&#xD;
    definitions within the enterprise) as well as industry or enterprise standards, models and assets in order speed up the&#xD;
    definition of a new IT architecture. Using&amp;nbsp;this bottom-up approach, Existing Architecture Analysis identifies and&#xD;
    validates candidate roles, functions, entities, locations&amp;nbsp;and flows. Technical constraints related to existing&#xD;
    systems should also be evaluated, again for speeding up the architecture process and for risk management&#xD;
    purposes.&amp;nbsp;Analyzing technical and enterprise (AD)&amp;nbsp;constraints should be done early in this analysis.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    If an Architectural Summary has already been defined, then this task (following the steps defined below) updates it&#xD;
    based upon the new and revised IT Architecture models.&#xD;
&lt;/p></refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription xmi:id="-rRRu1XOsyUH6cJ4nchSIYA" name="ea_business_mile,_jppE4NslEdy9s_D5ysfZfg" guid="-rRRu1XOsyUH6cJ4nchSIYA">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The architectural review has been completed, including any follow-on actions. This milestone is the formal end of the&#xD;
    development of the Business Perspective. The outputs from this Business level IT architecture are:&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Business Perspective&lt;/strong> - completed;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Architecture Decisions&lt;/strong> - stable and agreed by all stakeholders;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Architecture Glossary&lt;/strong> -&amp;nbsp;defined and refined;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Review Record&lt;/strong> - agreed, documented and follow-up actions completed.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The next steps are defined in the Review Record, and typically involve &lt;em>using&lt;/em> the architecture ... through the&#xD;
    normal enterprise IT management processes that use the architecture deliverables, which is&amp;nbsp;generically outlined&#xD;
    in: &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/deliveryprocesses/uam_it_architecture_in-ent_4608CDE7.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_YHA_kafREeS8vLSVufajPQ&quot;>Delivery Process: UAM in the Enterprise&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>The milestone marks the end of development of the Business Perspective, and the beginning of the next phase. A &quot;peer&#xD;
review&quot; was previously completed, and the just completed&amp;nbsp;&quot;stakeholder review&quot; ensured that the IT architecture meets&#xD;
their needs. The review follow-up is now complete and it is time to agree the next steps: how will this architecture&#xD;
perspective is to be used.</usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription xmi:id="--clH7ibihD3qWJcP7aY6lg" name="ea_system_mile,_uw-lsNslEdy9s_D5ysfZfg" guid="--clH7ibihD3qWJcP7aY6lg">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The architectural review has been completed, including any follow-on actions. This milestone is the formal end of the&#xD;
    development of the Logical Perspective. The outputs from this Logical level IT architecture are:&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Logical Perspective&lt;/strong> - completed;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Architecture Decisions&lt;/strong> - stable and agreed by all stakeholders;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Architecture Glossary&lt;/strong> -&amp;nbsp;defined and refined;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Review Record&lt;/strong> - agreed, documented and follow-up actions completed.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The next steps are defined in the Review Record, and typically involve &lt;em>using&lt;/em> the architecture ... through the&#xD;
    normal enterprise IT management processes that use the architecture deliverables, which is&amp;nbsp;generically outlined&#xD;
    in: &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/deliveryprocesses/uam_it_architecture_in-ent_4608CDE7.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_YHA_kafREeS8vLSVufajPQ&quot;>Delivery Process: UAM in the Enterprise&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>The milestone marks the end of development of the Logical Perspective, but more importantly the beginning of the next&#xD;
phase. A &quot;peer review&quot; was previously completed, and the just completed&amp;nbsp;&quot;stakeholder review&quot; ensured that the IT&#xD;
architecture meets their needs. The review follow-up is now complete and it is time to agree the next steps: how will this&#xD;
architecture perspective is to be used.</usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription xmi:id="-ADnkU1FfVV3KDGtHhFhMsA" name="ea_tech_mile,_7KzpINslEdy9s_D5ysfZfg" guid="-ADnkU1FfVV3KDGtHhFhMsA">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The architectural review has been completed, including any follow-on actions. This milestone is the formal end of the&#xD;
    development of the Technical Perspective. The outputs from this Technical level IT architecture are:&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Technical Perspective&lt;/strong> - completed;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Architecture Decisions&lt;/strong> - stable and agreed by all stakeholders;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Architecture Glossary&lt;/strong> -&amp;nbsp;defined and refined;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Review Record&lt;/strong> - agreed, documented and follow-up actions completed.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The next steps are defined in the Review Record, and typically involve &lt;em>using&lt;/em> the architecture ... through the&#xD;
    normal enterprise IT management processes that use the architecture deliverables, which is&amp;nbsp;generically outlined&#xD;
    in: &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/deliveryprocesses/uam_it_architecture_in-ent_4608CDE7.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_YHA_kafREeS8vLSVufajPQ&quot;>Delivery Process: UAM in the Enterprise&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>The milestone marks the end of development of the Technical Perspective , and the beginning of the next phase. A &quot;peer&#xD;
review&quot; was previously completed, and the just completed&amp;nbsp;&quot;stakeholder review&quot; ensured that the IT architecture meets&#xD;
their needs. The review follow-up is now complete and it is time to agree the next steps: how will this architecture&#xD;
perspective is to be used.</usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-fMOLafywndvEe-8mNyn94w" name="ea_org_review_review,_AkMdwdsoEdy9s_D5ysfZfg" guid="-fMOLafywndvEe-8mNyn94w"/>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-QCgzy7iNogUQeIbaPEGcLA" name="New Task Descriptor_3,_C1hnMdsoEdy9s_D5ysfZfg" guid="-QCgzy7iNogUQeIbaPEGcLA">
    <refinedDescription>The purpose of this task is to formally verify that the requirements defined for the business level view of the enterprise,&#xD;
domain or portion thereof, agree with the&amp;nbsp;stakeholder's (customer's) view of the system.</refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-vAA87olecz7FmaHYSLq8Ww" name="ea_review_req_system,_VSZVsdspEdy9s_D5ysfZfg" guid="-vAA87olecz7FmaHYSLq8Ww">
    <refinedDescription>The purpose of this task is to formally verify that the requirements defined for the system level view of the enteprise,&#xD;
domain or portion thereof, are understood and agree with the&amp;nbsp;stakeholder's (customer's) view of the system.</refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-QLKvxVP0c7xxLE5DuL3yDA" name="ea_review_business_models,_E0nxIdsoEdy9s_D5ysfZfg" guid="-QLKvxVP0c7xxLE5DuL3yDA">
    <refinedDescription>The purpose of this task is to formally verify that the model defined for the business level view of the enteprise, domain&#xD;
or portion thereof, agrees with the&amp;nbsp;enterprise's standards and that it also is compatible with the enterprise's&#xD;
strategic objectives. The architecture is also examined for consistency, completness, clarity and other aspects.</refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-Qms2W3Dp-SSZ5QI93e4mmQ" name="ea_review_req_tech,_upikINspEdy9s_D5ysfZfg" guid="-Qms2W3Dp-SSZ5QI93e4mmQ">
    <refinedDescription>The purpose of this task is to formally verify that the requirements defined for the technical level view of the enteprise,&#xD;
domain or portion thereof, are understood and agree with the&amp;nbsp;stakeholder's (customer's) and enterprise's view as well&#xD;
(enterprise standards for example).</refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-4GCLkSWgepxmgYM-IkSWYA" name="ea_review_system_models,_XQlgsNspEdy9s_D5ysfZfg" guid="-4GCLkSWgepxmgYM-IkSWYA">
    <refinedDescription>The purpose of this task is to formally verify that the model defined for the system level view of the enterprise, domain&#xD;
or portion thereof, agrees with the&amp;nbsp;enterprise's standards and that it also is compatible with the enterprise's&#xD;
strategic goals. The architecture is also examined for consistency, completness, clarity and other aspects.</refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-D217OYQ7dVszW0vZNE91Pg" name="New Task Descriptor_4,_yKIWAdspEdy9s_D5ysfZfg" guid="-D217OYQ7dVszW0vZNE91Pg">
    <refinedDescription>The purpose of this task is to formally verify that the model defined for the technology level view of the enterprise,&#xD;
domain or portion thereof, agrees with the&amp;nbsp;enterprise's standards and that it also is compatible with the enterprise's&#xD;
strategic direction. The architecture is also examined for consistency, completness, clarity and other aspects.</refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-OGh9fYhuCWP_GEh9SSwf3A" name="ea_agree_results_business,_qWKf4NsoEdy9s_D5ysfZfg" guid="-OGh9fYhuCWP_GEh9SSwf3A">
    <refinedDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    This task is focused on&amp;nbsp;following up on actions resulting from&amp;nbsp;a review of&amp;nbsp;the business level view of&#xD;
    the enterprise or domain architecture (or portion thereof). Actions are clarified if needed and assigned and tracked.&#xD;
&lt;/p></refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-H_MfhEckRIwyon6aMqQ00g" name="ea_agree_results_system,_YpsBodspEdy9s_D5ysfZfg" guid="-H_MfhEckRIwyon6aMqQ00g">
    <refinedDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    This task is focused on&amp;nbsp;following up on actions resulting from&amp;nbsp;a review of&amp;nbsp;the system level view of the&#xD;
    enterprise or domain architecture (or portion thereof). Actions are clarified if needed and assigned and tracked.&#xD;
&lt;/p></refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-UM1M65t7d76QPKouFI-72Q" name="ea_agree_results_tech,_0yp3cdspEdy9s_D5ysfZfg" guid="-UM1M65t7d76QPKouFI-72Q">
    <refinedDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    This task is focused on&amp;nbsp;following up on actions resulting from&amp;nbsp;a review of&amp;nbsp;the technical level view of&#xD;
    the enterprise or domain architecture (or portion thereof). Actions are clarified if needed and assigned and tracked.&#xD;
&lt;/p></refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription xmi:id="-x6Jf_yJMj5e-zCaZUOGXmw" name="ea_simple_architecture,_6TUQIMhQEdyU89e0dKAsrw" guid="-x6Jf_yJMj5e-zCaZUOGXmw">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Simple architecture models are produced quickly through leveraging existing documentation, domain expert knowledge and&#xD;
    through the reductions of rigor and detail in the models. This approach means that the objective, namely the eventual&#xD;
    usage of the resulting models should be well-defined prior to starting their development. This will focus the effort,&#xD;
    resulting in better quality models used for the intended purpose. However, using the models for other purposes is not&#xD;
    recommended, or should be undertaken with caution.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    It should be noted that due to the simplification and reduced vigor, the resulting models should be used for planning&#xD;
    and development of strategic directions with caution.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Simple architecture models are used for two reasons:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To expedite the development of the models due to time/resource constraints;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To aid in optimizing the&amp;nbsp;Logical or Technical architectures of the system.&lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></usageGuidance>
    <purpose>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_Delivery__Define_Simple&quot; name=&quot;XE_Delivery__Define_Simple&quot;>&lt;/a>Simple architectures are defined when time&#xD;
constraints or other factors require the speedy definition of the IT architecture, acknowledging that less rigor will be&#xD;
involved.</purpose>
    <howtoStaff>&lt;span&#xD;
style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Times New Roman','serif'; mso-ansi-language: EN-CA; mso-fareast-font-family: 'Times New Roman'; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA&quot;>&lt;font&#xD;
 face=&quot;Arial&quot;>This activity is best carried out by an individual or a small team (in the role of IT Architect, and usually&#xD;
guided by one or two individuals who have deep experience in architecting systems in the relevant domain) staffed by&#xD;
cross-functional team members. Issues that are typically architecturally important include structure, performance, scaling,&#xD;
distribution, or other speciality engineering requirements. Significant architectural constraints might also flow from&#xD;
physical and environmental requirements. The team should also include members with domain experience.&amp;nbsp;The team should&#xD;
also have experience with modeling, organization and layering.&lt;/font>&lt;/span></howtoStaff>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription xmi:id="-ETiA_HmGNOoncHpNcmV6_A" name="ea_document_existing,_EUJb4MhREdyU89e0dKAsrw" guid="-ETiA_HmGNOoncHpNcmV6_A">
    <mainDescription>The level of detail in the resulting &lt;em>as-is&lt;/em> architecture models is low, but should be to a level sufficient for the&#xD;
intended purpose. For example, if a migration plan is to be developed to a target architecture, the level of detail&#xD;
required should be estimated prior to development of the existing architecture models. This can be estimated based upon the&#xD;
divergence of the target from the existing; that is, the more the&amp;nbsp;divergence then more detail would be advantageous.&#xD;
This extra detail can be focused on the aspects or areas where the divergence is greatest.</mainDescription>
    <keyConsiderations>The level of detail in the resulting &lt;em>as-is&lt;/em> architecture models is low, but should be to a level sufficient for the&#xD;
intended purpose. For example, if a migration plan is to be developed to a target architecture, the level of detail&#xD;
required should be estimated prior to development of the existing architecture models. This can be estimated based upon the&#xD;
divergence of the target from the existing; that is, the more the&amp;nbsp;divergence then more detail would be advantageous.&#xD;
This extra detail can be focused on the aspects or areas where the divergence is greatest.</keyConsiderations>
    <usageGuidance>Generally existing IT environments are not documented architecturally (if documented at all). Therefore, in order to&#xD;
develop a migration plan to a target architecture (&lt;em>to-be&lt;/em> architecture) the existing environment (&lt;em>as-is&lt;/em>&#xD;
architecture) needs to be documented in a similar fashion to the target architecture, permitting a proper comparison (gap&#xD;
analysis) to be done.</usageGuidance>
    <purpose>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_Delivery__Existing&quot; name=&quot;XE_Delivery__Existing&quot;>&lt;/a> &#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Definition of the various system and technology level architectural views supports the analysis of the processes,&#xD;
    system structures&amp;nbsp;and other aspects, permitting optimizations to be discovered&amp;nbsp;along with a better&#xD;
    understanding of the business and the supporting systems and technologies. It also provides for the linkage of system&#xD;
    or technical level structures and decisions directly back to the business drivers. These models of the existing&#xD;
    environment are also used to support the modification of the environment or for more substantial evolution to a target&#xD;
    architecture through gap analysis and migration planning.&#xD;
&lt;/p></purpose>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription xmi:id="-dfoK3WRD2QXInWEae6N4xA" name="ea_simple_iteration,_QrEZkNpKEdyp3veHciZnuA" guid="-dfoK3WRD2QXInWEae6N4xA">
    <mainDescription>Multiple iterations are done to create the required Logical or&amp;nbsp;Technical level models, with enough detail defined to&#xD;
support the objectives of the project.</mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>Simple architectures are done only at the Logical or Technical levels, and therefore rely on existing models and&#xD;
descriptions of the business.</usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription xmi:id="-ChRMb2kqyZsvCK9CF0Jt4g" name="ea_architecture_review,_aBL6oMhSEdyU89e0dKAsrw" guid="-ChRMb2kqyZsvCK9CF0Jt4g">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    This activity is focused on organizing and doing&amp;nbsp;reviews of&amp;nbsp;the Business, Logical or Technical&amp;nbsp;level&#xD;
    views of the IT architecture. Appropriate materials are gathered, venues booked and participants informed.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    This review focuses on&amp;nbsp;the content of the architecture in terms of how accurately it captures the business and the&#xD;
    supporting solution, with stakeholders that have intimate knowledge of the area of the business in question being the&#xD;
    primary participants.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Actions are documented, assigned&amp;nbsp;and tracked.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Recommended as mandatory for&amp;nbsp;most architecture efforts, which provides valuable feedback to architects from peers&#xD;
    and stakeholders.&#xD;
&lt;/p></usageGuidance>
    <purpose>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_Delivery__Review&quot; name=&quot;XE_Delivery__Review&quot;>&lt;/a> &#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The purpose is to ensure that there is cohesion and agreement in the models, from the architecture perspective and get&#xD;
    agreement from stakeholders. And to also generally improve the quality of the architecture and the architects through&#xD;
    the provision of feedback.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Once an IT architecture perspective is completed, two types of reviews are undertaken:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        A&amp;nbsp;&lt;em>peer review&lt;/em> of the results is done prior to moving on to next steps, which focuses on the&#xD;
        consistency, completeness and cohesiveness of the architecture. This review is done at the end of the development&#xD;
        of the perspective, for example: &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
        href=&quot;./../../UAM/deliveryprocesses/uam_business_milestone_78D9E3AB.html&quot; guid=&quot;_Uw7RMN5nEdyg17nU3bVmlA&quot;>Milestone:&#xD;
        Business Perspective Milestone&lt;/a>.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        A second phase, the &lt;em>stakeholder review&lt;/em> described here, focuses on the content of the architecture in terms&#xD;
        of how accurately it captures the business, which normally involves a number of stakeholders that have intimate&#xD;
        knowledge of the area of the business in question, and at the correct level, namely Business, Logical&amp;nbsp;or&#xD;
        Technical.&amp;nbsp;This is the final &quot;approval&quot; step for the IT architecture perspective.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    These reviews document deficiencies, errors and omissions in a &quot;Review Record&quot;, which the architect then actions (i.e.,&#xD;
    models etc. are updated or changed as needed). The recommended next steps are also identified for later approval and&#xD;
    action.&#xD;
&lt;/p></purpose>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription xmi:id="-1nrUX54OCW24oAUWSa3bdw" name="ea_business_model,_LnOygMhSEdyU89e0dKAsrw" guid="-1nrUX54OCW24oAUWSa3bdw">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;span lang=&quot;EN-US&quot;>This phase has the following goals:&lt;/span>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Define a Business Entity Model for the system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Define a Business Process Model for the system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Define a Business Locations Model for the system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Define a Business Roles Model for the system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Update the Architecture Glossary and define Architectural Decisions as required.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    A number of tasks may be undertaken in parallel, such as the definition of the various aspects, and&amp;nbsp;Architectural&#xD;
    Decisions will also arise at any time. Once a complete perspective is defined a peer review is done to decide if the IT&#xD;
    architecture is complete, or if additional iterations are required.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Mandatory for any sort of IT architecture, except for definition of existing systems. It is key for business modeling&#xD;
    efforts aimed at redefining or improving the business model including data, processes, locations and roles aspects.&#xD;
    This phase is iterative in that, after the Business&amp;nbsp;Perspective is defined the architecture is assessed, followed&#xD;
    by another pass if&amp;nbsp;required. This work should be limited to one or two iterations.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;/p></usageGuidance>
    <purpose>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_Delivery__Business_Perspective&quot; name=&quot;XE_Delivery__Business_Perspective&quot;>&lt;/a> &#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Definition of the various Business level architectural views supports the analysis of the business processes and other&#xD;
    aspects, permitting optimizations to be discovered, along with&amp;nbsp;a better understanding of the business. It also&#xD;
    supports the linkage of Logical&amp;nbsp;and Technical level structures and decisions directly back to the business&#xD;
    drivers.&#xD;
&lt;/p></purpose>
    <howtoStaff>&lt;p class=&quot;Body&quot; style=&quot;MARGIN: 0in 0in 12pt&quot;>&#xD;
    These activities are best carried out by a small team staffed by cross-functional team members, lead by an IT&#xD;
    architect. Issues that are typically architecturally significant include data, process, locations, and roles. The team&#xD;
    should also include members with business domain experience&amp;nbsp;and ideally logical level &lt;span lang=&quot;EN-US&quot;&#xD;
    style=&quot;mso-ansi-language: EN-US&quot;>modelers&lt;/span>. The team should also have experience with model organization and&#xD;
    layering. From the provided&amp;nbsp;inputs, the team will need to be able to synthesize the models.&#xD;
&lt;/p></howtoStaff>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription xmi:id="-1R60JkMvUOoOp8_eW6KQ5Q" name="ea_system_model,_ptjs4MhSEdyU89e0dKAsrw" guid="-1R60JkMvUOoOp8_eW6KQ5Q">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;span lang=&quot;EN-US&quot;>This phase has the following goals:&lt;/span>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Define a Logical Entity Model for the system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Define a Logical Process Model for the system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Define a Logical Locations Model for the system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Define a Logical Roles Model for the system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Update the Architecture Glossary and define Architectural Decisions as required.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    A number of tasks may be undertaken in parallel, such as the definition of the various aspects, and&amp;nbsp;Architectural&#xD;
    Decisions will also arise at any time. Once a complete perspective is defined a peer review is done to decide if the IT&#xD;
    architecture is complete, or if additional iterations are required.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Recommended as mandatory for architecture efforts aimed at redefining or optimizing the business,&amp;nbsp;including the&#xD;
    data, processes, locations and actors/roles aspects. This phase is iterative, after each iteration is defined the&#xD;
    architecture is assessed, followed by another pass if&amp;nbsp;required. This work should be limited to two or three&#xD;
    iterations. The purpose is to define the Logical level architecture models.&#xD;
&lt;/p></usageGuidance>
    <purpose>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_Delivery__Logical_Perspective&quot; name=&quot;XE_Delivery__Logical_Perspective&quot;>&lt;/a> &#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Definition of the various Logical level architectural views supports the analysis of the processes, structures&amp;nbsp;and&#xD;
    other aspects, permitting optimizations to be discovered&amp;nbsp;along with a better understanding of the business and the&#xD;
    supporting information technologies. It also provides for the linkage of the Logical and Technical level structures and&#xD;
    decisions directly back to the business drivers.&#xD;
&lt;/p></purpose>
    <howtoStaff>&lt;p class=&quot;Body&quot; style=&quot;MARGIN: 0in 0in 12pt&quot;>&#xD;
    These activities are best carried out by a small team staffed by cross-functional team members, lead by an IT&#xD;
    architect. Issues that are typically architecturally significant include data, process, locations, and roles. The team&#xD;
    should also include members with business domain experience&amp;nbsp;and ideally logical level &lt;span lang=&quot;EN-US&quot;&#xD;
    style=&quot;mso-ansi-language: EN-US&quot;>modelers and IT experts&lt;/span>. The team should also have experience with model&#xD;
    organization and layering. From the provided&amp;nbsp;inputs, the team will need to be able to synthesize the models.&#xD;
&lt;/p></howtoStaff>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription xmi:id="-RRSV0IAWXsi-wgki-xJ8Gg" name="ea_technology_model,_tBZcMMhSEdyU89e0dKAsrw" guid="-RRSV0IAWXsi-wgki-xJ8Gg">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;span lang=&quot;EN-US&quot;>This phase has the following goals:&lt;/span>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Define a Technical Entity Model for the system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Define a Technical Process Model for the system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Define a Technical Locations Model for the system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Define a Technical Roles Model for the system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Update the Architecture Glossary and define Architectural Decisions as required.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;span lang=&quot;EN-US&quot;>A number of tasks may be undertaken in parallel, such as the definition of the various aspects,&#xD;
    and&amp;nbsp;Architectural Decisions will also arise at any time. Once a complete perspective is defined a peer review is&#xD;
    done to decide if the IT architecture is complete, or if additional iterations are required.&lt;/span>&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Mandatory for architecture efforts aimed at redefining or improving the&amp;nbsp;technical&amp;nbsp;model including data,&#xD;
    processes, locations and roles aspects. This phase is iterative, after each iteration is defined the architecture is&#xD;
    assessed, followed by another pass if&amp;nbsp;required. This work should be limited to two or three iterations. The&#xD;
    purpose is to define the Technical level architecture models.&#xD;
&lt;/p></usageGuidance>
    <purpose>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_Delivery__Technical_Perspective&quot; name=&quot;XE_Delivery__Technical_Perspective&quot;>&lt;/a>Definition of the various&#xD;
Technical level architectural views supports the analysis of the technical level processes, structures and other aspects,&#xD;
permitting optimizations to be discovered along with a better understanding of the&amp;nbsp;supporting information&#xD;
technologies. It also provides for the linkage of the Technical level structures and decisions directly back to the&#xD;
business drivers. &lt;br /></purpose>
    <howtoStaff>&lt;p class=&quot;Body&quot; style=&quot;MARGIN: 0in 0in 12pt&quot;>&#xD;
    These activities are best carried out by a small team staffed by cross-functional team members, lead by an IT&#xD;
    architect. Issues that are typically architecturally significant include data, process, locations, and roles. The team&#xD;
    should also include members with business domain experience&amp;nbsp;and ideally technical level &lt;span lang=&quot;EN-US&quot;&#xD;
    style=&quot;mso-ansi-language: EN-US&quot;>modelers and IT experts&lt;/span>. The team should also have experience with model&#xD;
    organization and layering. From the provided&amp;nbsp;inputs, the team will need to be able to synthesize the models.&#xD;
&lt;/p></howtoStaff>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription xmi:id="-2Mzf94QoQkIkTVXXT8RsGQ" name="ea_business_iteration,_Q5vkQN5nEdyg17nU3bVmlA" guid="-2Mzf94QoQkIkTVXXT8RsGQ">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Multiple iterations are done to create the required Business level models, with enough detail defined to support the&#xD;
    objectives of the IT architecture. Many activities can be done in parallel, but good communications is needed in order&#xD;
    to keep the models consistent, but good tool support makes this a non-issue. The following items are produced:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Business Entity Model for the system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Business Process Model for the system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Business Locations Model for the system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Business Roles Model for the system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Update the Architecture Glossary and define Architectural Decisions as required.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Once a complete perspective is defined a peer review is done to decide if the IT architecture is complete, or if&#xD;
    additional iterations are required.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The Business level is defined in an iterative manner. Note that&amp;nbsp;IT architectures are typically focused on and&#xD;
    driven by:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>The Business&lt;/strong> - the organization and its products and services. Fundamental changes to them and&#xD;
        their impact on the architecture are captured at the Business level.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Technology&lt;/strong> - technology typically has a large impact on the IT architecture, and may&amp;nbsp;require&#xD;
        the business to fundamentally change.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Business level architectures are typically centered upon&amp;nbsp;business processes, but they may also involve the&#xD;
    creation of totally new products or services and a set of new processes to support them. Technology may have a large&#xD;
    impact on the definition at the business level. Therefore, some knowledge of the proposed technologies and their&#xD;
    capabilities may be important when defining the Business level.&#xD;
&lt;/p></usageGuidance>
    <purpose>&lt;p class=&quot;Body&quot; style=&quot;MARGIN: 0in 0in 12pt&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;font face=&quot;Arial&quot;>&lt;span>Definition of the various Business level architectural views supports the analysis of the&#xD;
    business processes and other aspects, permitting optimizations to be discovered, along with&amp;nbsp;a better understanding&#xD;
    of the business. It also supports the linkage of Logical&amp;nbsp;and Technical level structures and decisions directly&#xD;
    back to the business drivers.&lt;/span>&lt;/font> The Architectural Decision taken at the Business level will typically&#xD;
    involve structural decisions regarding processes.&#xD;
&lt;/p></purpose>
    <howtoStaff>&lt;p class=&quot;Body&quot; style=&quot;MARGIN: 0in 0in 12pt&quot;>&#xD;
    These activities are best carried out by a small team staffed by cross-functional team members, lead by an IT&#xD;
    architect. Issues that are typically architecturally significant include data, process, locations, and roles. The team&#xD;
    should include members with business domain experience&amp;nbsp;and also &lt;span lang=&quot;EN-US&quot;&#xD;
    style=&quot;mso-ansi-language: EN-US&quot;>modelers&lt;/span>. The team should also have experience with model organization and&#xD;
    layering. From the provided&amp;nbsp;inputs, the team will need to be able to synthesize the architecture views.&#xD;
&lt;/p></howtoStaff>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription xmi:id="-v90KkoYOgJI4SIEtaQz1jg" name="New Milestone,_Uw7RMN5nEdyg17nU3bVmlA" guid="-v90KkoYOgJI4SIEtaQz1jg">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The architectural review done in&amp;nbsp;the Business Perspective context involves ensuring that the architecture&#xD;
    addresses the business needs and fits in with the enterprise direction in the long-term. Scenarios may be used to test&#xD;
    the architecture. If there is a problem in the direction taken by the architecture (which needs to be documented and&#xD;
    justified)&amp;nbsp;in terms of the enterprise long-term objectives or standards then management will review and bless this&#xD;
    deviation in direction.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h5>&#xD;
    Evaluation Criteria:&#xD;
&lt;/h5>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Business goals and strategies have been&amp;nbsp;reviewed and summarized.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/workproducts/uam_arch_context-objectives_874E760A.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_tjC3QMOdEdyILM4NThxMFg&quot;>Context and Objectives&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;has been defined.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The &lt;em>to-be&lt;/em> business has been modeled.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Agreement on defined Architectural Decisions has been reached.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The&amp;nbsp;&lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/workproducts/uam_perspective_business_FFFBC993.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_ifSCYNQFEdyTfZVjf0InKw&quot;>Business Perspective&lt;/a> has been defined and agreed (i.e., the architect &lt;em>peer&#xD;
        review&lt;/em> completed).&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Major risks / issues have been addressed and the stakeholders agreed with the resolutions.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;h5>&#xD;
    Main Artifacts:&#xD;
&lt;/h5>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Business Perspective&lt;/strong> - completed;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Architecture Decisions&lt;/strong> - stable and agreed by all stakeholders;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Architecture Glossary&lt;/strong> -&amp;nbsp;defined and refined;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Review Record&lt;/strong> - issues agreed, documented and required updates completed.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Typically a &quot;stakeholder review&quot; is done once this formal peer review has been completed. See: &lt;a&#xD;
    class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/deliveryprocesses/uam_architecture_review_524E0258.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_aBL6oMhSEdyU89e0dKAsrw&quot;>Phase: Review the Architecture&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>The milestone marks the end of development of the Business Perspective, but more importantly the beginning of the next&#xD;
phase. This &quot;peer review&quot;&amp;nbsp; ensures that the IT architecture is clear, consistent and is in-line with enterprise&#xD;
standards. The architecture is developed for a purpose, now is the time to review what was produced and then agree the next&#xD;
steps: how will this architecture view be used.</usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="--hXGIpLqyqKMF-y2WaiKZQ" name="ea_scan_ads_business,_ySvu4d7sEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="--hXGIpLqyqKMF-y2WaiKZQ">
    <usageGuidance>Scanning Architectural Decisions helps in setting the stage and context for the business architecture effort to come. This&#xD;
effort will either use these decisions or modify them as required. ADs are scanned, and an AD Summary produced, to ensure&#xD;
that this is available for stakeholders during the development of the perspective.</usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-1SswitnaNeB7R2l9bN4GuA" name="ea_ccbv_business_model,_pRiXoN7tEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="-1SswitnaNeB7R2l9bN4GuA">
    <usageGuidance>Capturing a common vocabulary is extremely important when developing architectures. This helps in developing the common&#xD;
understanding and agreed and more precise terminology to be used in describing the business (and eventually the more&#xD;
technical views of the business). The Architecture Glossary for the project is augmented as required during the work on the&#xD;
Business Perspective.</usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription xmi:id="-OhYyBeLihvWnxHfZFNUx9w" name="ea_system_milestone,_slNTkN8IEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="-OhYyBeLihvWnxHfZFNUx9w">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The architectural review done in&amp;nbsp;the Logical Perspective context involves ensuring that the architecture addresses&#xD;
    the enterprise IT strategy and direction and supports the enterprise's business strategy and direction. Scenarios may&#xD;
    be used to test the architecture. If there is a problem in the direction taken by the architecture (which need to be&#xD;
    documented and justified in ADs)&amp;nbsp;in terms of the enterprise long-term objectives or standards, and&amp;nbsp;then&#xD;
    management will&amp;nbsp;review and bless this deviation in direction.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h5>&#xD;
    Evaluation Criteria:&#xD;
&lt;/h5>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The Logical Perspective requirements are documented and stable.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The &lt;em>to-be&lt;/em> systems have been modeled.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/workproducts/uam_perspective_logical_40FE04D0.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_Py-hINT-EdyakOJbsHza1A&quot;>Logical Perspective&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;has been defined (i.e., the architect &lt;em>peer&#xD;
        review&lt;/em> completed).&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Agreement on defined Architectural Decisions has been reached.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The&amp;nbsp;terminology (both Business and Logical levels) have been defined and agreed.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Major risks / issues have been addressed and the stakeholders agreed with the resolutions.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;h5>&#xD;
    Main Artifacts:&#xD;
&lt;/h5>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Logical Perspective&lt;/strong> - completed&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Architecture Decisions&lt;/strong> - stable and agreed by all stakeholders&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Glossary&lt;/strong> -&amp;nbsp;defined and refined&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Review Record&lt;/strong> - agreed and documented&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Typically a &quot;stakeholder review&quot; is done once this formal peer review has been completed. See: &lt;a&#xD;
    class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/deliveryprocesses/uam_architecture_review_524E0258.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_aBL6oMhSEdyU89e0dKAsrw&quot;>Phase: Review the Architecture&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>The milestone marks the end of development of the Logical Perspective, and the beginning of the next phase. This &quot;peer&#xD;
review&quot;&amp;nbsp; ensures that the IT architecture is clear, consistent and is in-line with enterprise standards. The&#xD;
architecture is developed for a purpose, now is the time to review what was produced and then agree the next steps: how&#xD;
will this architecture view be used.</usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription xmi:id="-L_HjLcmRl7uYJoHSdDbzxQ" name="ea_system_model_iteration,_lACR8N8IEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="-L_HjLcmRl7uYJoHSdDbzxQ">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Multiple iterations are done to create the required Logical level models, with enough detail defined to support the&#xD;
    objectives of the exercise. Many activities can be done in parallel, but good communications is needed in order to keep&#xD;
    the models consistent, but good tool support makes this a non-issue. The following items are produced:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Logical Entity Model for the system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Logical Process Model for the system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Logical Locations Model for the system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Logical Roles Model for the system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Update the Architecture Glossary and define Architectural Decisions as required.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Once a complete perspective is defined a peer review is done to decide if the IT architecture is complete, or if&#xD;
    additional iterations are required.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The Logical level is defined in an iterative manner. Note that&amp;nbsp;IT architectures are typically focused on and&#xD;
    driven by:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>The Business&lt;/strong> - the organization and its products and/or services;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Technology&lt;/strong> - the technology that supports the business typically has a large impact on the IT&#xD;
        architecture.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Logical level architectures are typically centered upon technology choices and patterns that likely affect business&#xD;
    processes.&amp;nbsp;The architecture&amp;nbsp;may also involve the creation of totally new products or services and a set of&#xD;
    new processes to support them. Technology may have a large impact on the architecture. Therefore,&amp;nbsp;the proposed&#xD;
    (generic) technologies and their capabilities are important when defining the Logical level.&#xD;
&lt;/p></usageGuidance>
    <purpose>&lt;p class=&quot;Body&quot; style=&quot;MARGIN: 0in 0in 12pt&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;font face=&quot;Arial&quot;>&lt;span>Definition of the various Logical level architectural views supports the analysis of the&#xD;
    business processes, generic technology choices,&amp;nbsp;and other aspects, permitting optimizations to be discovered. A&#xD;
    better understanding of the business and how technology supports it is also developed. The&amp;nbsp;Logical&amp;nbsp;(and&#xD;
    Technical) level structures and decisions are linked&amp;nbsp;directly back to the business drivers through the Business&#xD;
    level.&lt;/span>&lt;/font> The Architectural Decision taken at the Logical level will typically involve choices regarding&#xD;
    generic technology and architectural patterns.&#xD;
&lt;/p></purpose>
    <howtoStaff>&lt;p class=&quot;Body&quot; style=&quot;MARGIN: 0in 0in 12pt&quot;>&#xD;
    These activities are best carried out by a small team staffed by cross-functional team members, lead by an IT&#xD;
    architect. Issues that are typically architecturally significant include&amp;nbsp;process, locations, and roles, along with&#xD;
    the generic technology choices. The team should include members with business domain experience&amp;nbsp;and ideally&#xD;
    logical level &lt;span lang=&quot;EN-US&quot; style=&quot;mso-ansi-language: EN-US&quot;>modelers and IT experts as required&lt;/span>. The team&#xD;
    should have experience with model organization and layering.&amp;nbsp;From the provided&amp;nbsp;inputs, the team will need to&#xD;
    be able to synthesize the architecture views.&#xD;
&lt;/p></howtoStaff>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription xmi:id="-xqZEOvFCBcWRSWZgmcnakQ" name="New Iteration,_x-13cN8YEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="-xqZEOvFCBcWRSWZgmcnakQ">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Multiple iterations are done to create the required Technical level models, with enough detail defined to support the&#xD;
    objectives of the exercise. Many activities can be done in parallel, but good communications is needed in order to keep&#xD;
    the models consistent, but good tool support makes this a non-issue. The following items are produced:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Technical Entity Model for the system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Technical Process Model for the system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Technical Locations Model for the system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Technical Roles Model for the system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Update the Architecture Glossary and define Architectural Decisions as required.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Once a complete perspective is defined a peer review is done to decide if the IT architecture is complete, or if&#xD;
    additional iterations are required.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The Technical level is defined in an iterative manner. Note that&amp;nbsp;IT architectures are typically focused on and&#xD;
    driven by:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>The Business&lt;/strong> - the organization and its products and services;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Technology&lt;/strong> - the technology that supports the business typically has a large impact on the IT&#xD;
        architecture.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Technical level architectures are typically centered upon specific technology choices and patterns. Generic choices&#xD;
    made at the Logical level likely affected business process definitions, now the detailed influences&amp;nbsp;of the&#xD;
    technologies chosen are addressed.&amp;nbsp;Also important at the Technical level are the choices around IT security an&#xD;
    also the Actor/Roles model and how the user interface supports end-to-end business processes.&#xD;
&lt;/p></usageGuidance>
    <purpose>&lt;p class=&quot;Body&quot; style=&quot;MARGIN: 0in 0in 12pt&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;font face=&quot;Arial&quot;>&lt;span>Definition of the various Technical level architectural views supports the analysis of the&#xD;
    business processes, specific technology choices,&amp;nbsp;and other aspects, permitting optimizations to be discovered. A&#xD;
    better understanding of the business and how the specific technology chosen supports it is also developed.&#xD;
    The&amp;nbsp;Technical level structures and decisions are linked&amp;nbsp;directly back to the business drivers through the&#xD;
    Logical and Business levels.&lt;/span>&lt;/font> The Architectural Decision taken at the Technical level will typically&#xD;
    involve choices regarding the specifics of the&amp;nbsp;technology and details of the application of architectural&#xD;
    patterns.&#xD;
&lt;/p></purpose>
    <howtoStaff>&lt;p class=&quot;Body&quot; style=&quot;MARGIN: 0in 0in 12pt&quot;>&#xD;
    These activities are best carried out by a small team staffed by cross-functional team members, lead by an IT&#xD;
    architect. Issues that are typically architecturally significant include data, process, locations, and roles. The team&#xD;
    should also include members with business domain experience&amp;nbsp;and ideally logical level &lt;span lang=&quot;EN-US&quot;&#xD;
    style=&quot;mso-ansi-language: EN-US&quot;>modelers&lt;/span>. The team should also have experience with model organization and&#xD;
    layering. From the provided&amp;nbsp;inputs, the team will need to be able to synthesize the architecture views.&#xD;
&lt;/p></howtoStaff>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription xmi:id="-Z55FTPAQt_h0oFzubwhcpg" name="New Milestone,_8iFMsN8YEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="-Z55FTPAQt_h0oFzubwhcpg">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The architectural review done in&amp;nbsp;the Technical Perspective&amp;nbsp;context involves ensuring that the architecture&#xD;
    addresses the enterprise IT strategy and direction and supports the enterprise's business strategy and direction.&#xD;
    Consideration of tactical IT decisions (hopefully documented in Architectural Decisions) need to also be factored into&#xD;
    the review, likely affecting the definition of next steps.&amp;nbsp;Scenarios may be used to test the architecture. If&#xD;
    there is a problem in the direction taken by the architecture (which need to be documented and justified in&#xD;
    ADs)&amp;nbsp;in terms of the enterprise long-term objectives or standards then management will review and bless this&#xD;
    deviation in direction.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h5>&#xD;
    Evaluation Criteria:&#xD;
&lt;/h5>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The Technical Requirements are documented and stable.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The &lt;em>to-be&lt;/em> technical architecture has been modeled.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/workproducts/uam_perspective_technical_BED9D321.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_Tms8ENWbEdyLINQdtlJihw&quot;>Technical Perspective&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;has been defined (i.e, the architect &lt;em>peer&#xD;
        review&lt;/em> is completed).&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Agreement on defined Architectural Decisions has been reached.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The&amp;nbsp;terminology (Business, Logical&amp;nbsp;and Technical levels) have been defined and agreed.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Major risks / issues have been addressed and the stakeholders agreed with the resolutions.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;h5>&#xD;
    Main Artifacts:&#xD;
&lt;/h5>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Technical Perspective&lt;/strong> - completed;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Architecture Decisions&lt;/strong> - stable and agreed by all stakeholders;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Business, Logical and Technical Level Architecture Glossaries&lt;/strong> -&amp;nbsp;defined and refined;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Review Record&lt;/strong> -&amp;nbsp;agreed and documented.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Typically a &quot;stakeholder review&quot; is done once this formal peer review has been completed. See: &lt;a&#xD;
    class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/deliveryprocesses/uam_architecture_review_524E0258.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_aBL6oMhSEdyU89e0dKAsrw&quot;>Phase: Review the Architecture&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>The milestone marks the end of development of the Technical Perspective, and the beginning of the next phase. This &quot;peer&#xD;
review&quot;&amp;nbsp; ensures that the IT architecture is clear, consistent and is in-line with enterprise standards. The&#xD;
architecture is developed for a purpose, now is the time to review what was produced and then agree the next steps: how&#xD;
will this architecture view be used.</usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-2niQsUyEap4r5-cc7YEUwg" name="ea_define_ad_existing,_TRNxEdp5EdyFbt-dvvmLCA" guid="-2niQsUyEap4r5-cc7YEUwg">
    <usageGuidance>Architectural Decisions are created as required during the development of the IT architecture. They capture the essence of&#xD;
the architecture ... the main decisions made and required to defined the architecture.</usageGuidance>
    <refinedDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The purpose of this activity is to create an Architecture Decision (AD), specifically to:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Define the context of the problem, issue or decision;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Define the constraints, imposed by existing architecture, enterprise standards or others;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Define the rationale for the decision, through a well researched summary of the facts;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Extract the implications of the AD, on current systems, future systems, support aspects and other aspects;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Define the specifics of the decision.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    This activity results in the production of an AD. The diagram illustrates the main inputs and outputs of this activity&#xD;
    as hinted at above. A problem context helps to define the scope of the AD, and the constraints (imposed by technology,&#xD;
    the current situation, etc.) along with the rational (that is very much local to the business and the context) help in&#xD;
    arriving at and defining the decision. Implications of this decision, on the business and the current situation, are&#xD;
    also extracted and defined.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;blockquote style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;p>&#xD;
        &lt;img alt=&quot;AD Rationale&quot; src=&quot;./../../UAM/tasks/./resources/AD_rationale.png&quot; />&#xD;
    &lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;/blockquote>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    This is explained in more detail in the descriptions of the steps involved.&#xD;
&lt;/p></refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription xmi:id="-mOYMZz7sO4Za-RBjMj2j9w" name="New Milestone,_Uw7RMN5nEdyg17nU3bVmlA" guid="-mOYMZz7sO4Za-RBjMj2j9w">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The architectural review done in&amp;nbsp;the Business Perspective context involves ensuring that the architecture&#xD;
    addresses the business needs and fits in with the enterprise direction in the long-term. Scenarios may be used to test&#xD;
    the architecture. If there is a problem in the direction taken by the architecture (which needs to be documented and&#xD;
    justified)&amp;nbsp;in terms of the enterprise long-term objectives or standards then management will review and bless this&#xD;
    deviation in direction.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h5>&#xD;
    Evaluation Criteria:&#xD;
&lt;/h5>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Business goals and strategies have been&amp;nbsp;reviewed and summarized.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/workproducts/uam_arch_context-objectives_874E760A.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_tjC3QMOdEdyILM4NThxMFg&quot;>Context and Objectives&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;has been defined.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The &lt;em>to-be&lt;/em> business has been modeled.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Agreement on defined Architectural Decisions has been reached.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The&amp;nbsp;&lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/workproducts/uam_perspective_business_FFFBC993.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_ifSCYNQFEdyTfZVjf0InKw&quot;>Business Perspective&lt;/a> has been defined and agreed (i.e., the architect &lt;em>peer&#xD;
        review&lt;/em> completed).&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Major risks / issues have been addressed and the stakeholders agreed with the resolutions.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;h5>&#xD;
    Main Artifacts:&#xD;
&lt;/h5>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Business Perspective&lt;/strong> - completed;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Architecture Decisions&lt;/strong> - stable and agreed by all stakeholders;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Architecture Glossary&lt;/strong> -&amp;nbsp;defined and refined;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Review Record&lt;/strong> - issues agreed, documented and required updates completed.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Typically a &quot;stakeholder review&quot; is done once this peer review has been completed. See: &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../UAM/deliveryprocesses/uam_architecture_review_524E0258.html&quot; guid=&quot;_aBL6oMhSEdyU89e0dKAsrw&quot;>Phase: Review&#xD;
    the Architecture&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>The milestone marks the end of development of the Business Perspective, but more importantly the beginning of the next&#xD;
phase. This &quot;peer review&quot;&amp;nbsp; ensures that the IT architecture is clear, consistent and is in-line with enterprise&#xD;
standards. The architecture is developed for a purpose, now is the time to review what was produced and then agree the next&#xD;
steps: how will this architecture view be used.</usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription xmi:id="-A5AO3I7JTg9Ot1ya2gEQYw" name="ea_system_milestone,_slNTkN8IEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="-A5AO3I7JTg9Ot1ya2gEQYw">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The architectural review done in&amp;nbsp;the Logical Perspective context involves ensuring that the architecture addresses&#xD;
    the enterprise IT strategy and direction and supports the enterprise's business strategy and direction. Scenarios may&#xD;
    be used to test the architecture. If there is a problem in the direction taken by the architecture (which need to be&#xD;
    documented and justified in ADs)&amp;nbsp;in terms of the enterprise long-term objectives or standards, and&amp;nbsp;then&#xD;
    management will&amp;nbsp;review and bless this deviation in direction.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h5>&#xD;
    Evaluation Criteria:&#xD;
&lt;/h5>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The Logical Perspective requirements are documented and stable.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The &lt;em>to-be&lt;/em> systems have been modeled.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/workproducts/uam_perspective_logical_40FE04D0.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_Py-hINT-EdyakOJbsHza1A&quot;>Logical Perspective&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;has been defined (i.e., the architect &lt;em>peer&#xD;
        review&lt;/em> completed).&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Agreement on defined Architectural Decisions has been reached.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The&amp;nbsp;terminology (both Business and Logical levels) have been defined and agreed.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Major risks / issues have been addressed and the stakeholders agreed with the resolutions.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;h5>&#xD;
    Main Artifacts:&#xD;
&lt;/h5>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Logical Perspective&lt;/strong> - completed&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Architecture Decisions&lt;/strong> - stable and agreed by all stakeholders&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Glossary&lt;/strong> -&amp;nbsp;defined and refined&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Review Record&lt;/strong> - agreed and documented&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Typically a &quot;stakeholder review&quot; is done once this peer review has been completed. See: &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../UAM/deliveryprocesses/uam_architecture_review_524E0258.html&quot; guid=&quot;_aBL6oMhSEdyU89e0dKAsrw&quot;>Phase: Review&#xD;
    the Architecture&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>The milestone marks the end of development of the Logical Perspective, and the beginning of the next phase. This &quot;peer&#xD;
review&quot;&amp;nbsp; ensures that the IT architecture is clear, consistent and is in-line with enterprise standards. The&#xD;
architecture is developed for a purpose, now is the time to review what was produced and then agree the next steps: how&#xD;
will this architecture view be used.</usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription xmi:id="-Ze-pTzwtAbaAaujASLjUGg" name="New Milestone,_8iFMsN8YEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="-Ze-pTzwtAbaAaujASLjUGg">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The architectural review done in&amp;nbsp;the Technical Perspective&amp;nbsp;context involves ensuring that the architecture&#xD;
    addresses the enterprise IT strategy and direction and supports the enterprise's business strategy and direction.&#xD;
    Consideration of tactical IT decisions (hopefully documented in Architectural Decisions) need to also be factored into&#xD;
    the review, likely affecting the definition of next steps.&amp;nbsp;Scenarios may be used to test the architecture. If&#xD;
    there is a problem in the direction taken by the architecture (which need to be documented and justified in&#xD;
    ADs)&amp;nbsp;in terms of the enterprise long-term objectives or standards then management will review and bless this&#xD;
    deviation in direction.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h5>&#xD;
    Evaluation Criteria:&#xD;
&lt;/h5>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The Technical Requirements are documented and stable.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The &lt;em>to-be&lt;/em> technical architecture has been modeled.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/workproducts/uam_perspective_technical_BED9D321.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_Tms8ENWbEdyLINQdtlJihw&quot;>Technical Perspective&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;has been defined (i.e, the architect &lt;em>peer&#xD;
        review&lt;/em> is completed).&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Agreement on defined Architectural Decisions has been reached.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The&amp;nbsp;terminology (Business, Logical&amp;nbsp;and Technical levels) have been defined and agreed.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Major risks / issues have been addressed and the stakeholders agreed with the resolutions.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;h5>&#xD;
    Main Artifacts:&#xD;
&lt;/h5>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Technical Perspective&lt;/strong> - completed&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Architecture Decisions&lt;/strong> - stable and agreed by all stakeholders&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Business, Logical and Technical Level Architecture Glossaries&lt;/strong> -&amp;nbsp;defined and refined&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Review Record&lt;/strong> -&amp;nbsp;agreed and documented&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Typically a &quot;stakeholder review&quot; is done once this peer review has been completed. See: &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../UAM/deliveryprocesses/uam_architecture_review_524E0258.html&quot; guid=&quot;_aBL6oMhSEdyU89e0dKAsrw&quot;>Phase: Review&#xD;
    the Architecture&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>The milestone marks the end of development of the Technical Perspective, and the beginning of the next phase. This &quot;peer&#xD;
review&quot;&amp;nbsp; ensures that the IT architecture is clear, consistent and is in-line with enterprise standards. The&#xD;
architecture is developed for a purpose, now is the time to review what was produced and then agree the next steps: how&#xD;
will this architecture view be used.</usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription xmi:id="-N-1IuBnYmK3_UC6FfiBbLA" name="ea_develop_migration_plan,_6BTYksH5EdyMpOiGFnM_WA" guid="-N-1IuBnYmK3_UC6FfiBbLA">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    To develop a migration plan a current environment is compared with a target architecture and the differences noted.&#xD;
    Knowledge of dependencies between components, technologies, processes and systems, among other aspects, is then used to&#xD;
    order these steps into a logical sequence of activities, with the end result being the enterprise's environment ending&#xD;
    up in the target state as defined by the target enterprise architecture.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Once the migration plan is defined, it is then up to the organization, through its management and planning processes,&#xD;
    to execute based upon this plan. Each enterprise has its own governance processes; for the business and for the&#xD;
    associated IT systems. A separate generic governance process has been defined within UAM that specifies where and how&#xD;
    to integrate UAM within these pre-existing enterprise management&amp;nbsp;processes. This &quot;Delivery Process&quot; is to be&#xD;
    adapted and integrated into the enteprise's processes. See:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../UAM/deliveryprocesses/uam_it_architecture_in-ent_4608CDE7.html&quot; guid=&quot;_YHA_kafREeS8vLSVufajPQ&quot;>Delivery&#xD;
    Process: UAM in the Enterprise&lt;/a>&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <keyConsiderations>Once the migration plan is defined, it is then up to the organization, through its management and planning processes, to&#xD;
execute based upon this plan. Each enterprise has its own governance processes; for the business and for the associated IT&#xD;
systems. A separate generic governance process has been defined within UAM that specifies where and how to integrate UAM&#xD;
within these pre-existing enterprise management&amp;nbsp;processes. This &quot;Delivery Process&quot; is to be adapted and integrated&#xD;
into the enteprise's processes. See:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
href=&quot;./../../UAM/deliveryprocesses/uam_it_architecture_in-ent_4608CDE7.html&quot; guid=&quot;_YHA_kafREeS8vLSVufajPQ&quot;>Delivery&#xD;
Process: UAM in the Enterprise&lt;/a></keyConsiderations>
    <usageGuidance>Migration planning is done to define the steps (normally a series of projects) necessary to move the enterprises&#xD;
information technology environment from an existing state to a target state as defined by a target architecture.</usageGuidance>
    <howtoStaff>&lt;p class=&quot;Body&quot; style=&quot;MARGIN: 0in 0in 12pt&quot;>&#xD;
    These activities are best carried out by a small team staffed by cross-functional team members.&amp;nbsp;The team&#xD;
    should&amp;nbsp;include members with domain and specifically the existing environment and&amp;nbsp;who can identify key&#xD;
    dependencies, ideally at the business, system and technology levels. The team should also have some knowledge of&#xD;
    project planning.&#xD;
&lt;/p></howtoStaff>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription xmi:id="-APe0FoaggMCHDyk2SU26xQ" name="New Milestone,_Uw7RMN5nEdyg17nU3bVmlA" guid="-APe0FoaggMCHDyk2SU26xQ">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The architectural review done in&amp;nbsp;the Business View&amp;nbsp;context involves ensuring that the architecture addresses&#xD;
    the business need and fits in with the enterprise direction in the long-term. Scenarios may be used to test the&#xD;
    architecture. If there is a problem in the direction taken by the architecture (which needs to be documented and&#xD;
    justified)&amp;nbsp;in terms of the enterprise long-term objectives or standards then management will review and bless this&#xD;
    deviation in direction.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h5>&#xD;
    Evaluation Criteria:&#xD;
&lt;/h5>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Business goals and strategies have been&amp;nbsp;reviewed and summarized.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../Enterprise_Architecture/workproducts/ea_business_scope_874E760A.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_tjC3QMOdEdyILM4NThxMFg&quot;>Business Scope&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;has been defined.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The to-be business has been modelled.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Agreement on a refined Business Vision has been reached.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Agreement on defined Architectural Decisions has been reached.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The&amp;nbsp;&lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
        href=&quot;./../../Enterprise_Architecture/workproducts/ea_ent_business_model_FFFBC993.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_ifSCYNQFEdyTfZVjf0InKw&quot;>Enterprise Business Model&lt;/a> has been defined and agreed, architect peer review&#xD;
        completed.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Major risks / issues have been addressed and the stakeholders agreed with the resolutions.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;h5>&#xD;
    Main Artifacts:&#xD;
&lt;/h5>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../Enterprise_Architecture/workproducts/ea_ent_business_model_FFFBC993.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_ifSCYNQFEdyTfZVjf0InKw&quot;>Enterprise Business Model&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;- completed&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Architecture Decisions - stable and agreed by all stakeholders&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Business Glossary -&amp;nbsp;defined and refined&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Review Results agreed and documented&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>The milestone marks the end of development of the Business Level view, but more importantly the beginning of the next&#xD;
phase. The architecture is developed for a purpose, now is the time to review what was produced and then agree the next&#xD;
steps: how will this architecture view be used.</usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription xmi:id="-AWnojNYWfNXwwdQIJY6sXg" name="New Activity,_-odJgaS6EeS1o4_8kucAIw" guid="-AWnojNYWfNXwwdQIJY6sXg">
    <usageGuidance>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The first thing to be done when starting into a new IT architecture project is to define the context, scope, and&#xD;
    objectives. This ensures that the project is bounded and that the objectives are clearly understood. This activity is&#xD;
    only done for the following types of projects:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Define a Simple Architecture;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Document an Existing Architecture;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Document a Complex or Moderate Architecture (only at the&amp;nbsp;initial Business level).&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    This step ensure that the project get off on the right foot, with clear objectives and with a clear scope defined.&#xD;
&lt;/p></usageGuidance>
    <purpose>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_Delivery__Context_and_Objectives&quot; name=&quot;XE_Delivery__Context_and_Objectives&quot;>&lt;/a>Definition the Context and&#xD;
Objectives ensures that the IT architecture project gets off on the right foot.</purpose>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription xmi:id="-3qz_zajNxY4nhPXlC1jINg" name="New Milestone,_WjmhwKTAEeS1o4_8kucAIw" guid="-3qz_zajNxY4nhPXlC1jINg">
    <usageGuidance>The definition and review of the context, scope and objectives of the IT architecture project should not be an onerous&#xD;
task. The&amp;nbsp;review typically results in approval, but if not the stakeholders will provide the detailed direction&#xD;
necessary to the IT architect in order to obtain approval.</usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription xmi:id="-MJ0jzhEaIA1tOkDTPy0CYA" name="New Milestone,_0HxZAKcrEeS8vLSVufajPQ" guid="-MJ0jzhEaIA1tOkDTPy0CYA">
    <keyConsiderations>The decision of this &lt;em>go&lt;/em> / &lt;em>no-go&lt;/em> review is recorded in a Review Record, which records all of the work done&#xD;
during this review. The Problem Report (if follow-on from a solution impact analysis) or the Architectural Decision (if&#xD;
follow-on from an analysis of business opportunities) document is also updated.</keyConsiderations>
    <usageGuidance>&lt;p>&#xD;
    If the impact of the introduction of new technology or the solution to a problem is low enough then this management&#xD;
    review milestone may be bypassed (e.g., the cost/effort is below a pre-defined threshold).&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Typically the manager of the system, and other key stakeholders, need to be involved in this milestone review.&#xD;
    Investment, project, or program management people likely need to be involved as well.&#xD;
&lt;/p></usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription xmi:id="-fz7M3GHcH0cq_qyjGkg1ag" name="New Milestone,_pr2PoKfOEeS8vLSVufajPQ" guid="-fz7M3GHcH0cq_qyjGkg1ag">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Typically the follow-on actions involve engaging management in executing the next steps. However, each enterprise has&#xD;
    its own governance processes; for the business and for the associated IT systems. A separate generic governance process&#xD;
    has been defined within UAM that specifies where and how to integrate UAM within these pre-existing enterprise&#xD;
    management&amp;nbsp;processes. This &quot;Delivery Process&quot; is to be adapted and integrated into the enteprise's processes.&#xD;
    See:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/deliveryprocesses/uam_it_architecture_in-ent_4608CDE7.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_YHA_kafREeS8vLSVufajPQ&quot;>Delivery Process: UAM in the Enterprise&lt;/a>&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>Once the recommendations and actions are recorded and agreed by participants, these recommendations need to be reviewed and&#xD;
approved by IT managers and other senior stakeholders. These next steps (defined in the Review Record) are typically&#xD;
actioned through the normal enterprise IT management processes, generically outlined in: &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
href=&quot;./../../UAM/deliveryprocesses/uam_it_architecture_in-ent_4608CDE7.html&quot; guid=&quot;_YHA_kafREeS8vLSVufajPQ&quot;>Delivery&#xD;
Process: UAM in the Enterprise&lt;/a>.</usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription xmi:id="-zVj917OQ7K0AfyowsCq29A" name="ea_maint_arch,_iG3b4ENgEeShYIpiBstbOQ" guid="-zVj917OQ7K0AfyowsCq29A">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The three possible triggers for updates (i.e.,&amp;nbsp;business change, technology change or problem)&amp;nbsp;are integrated&#xD;
    into the process. The included activities for all possible paths are:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Determine Solution &amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;Impact&lt;/strong>  a solution to a problem is agreed and defined, and then the&#xD;
        impact is determined in terms of the models requiring updates. Impacts to Business models will require updates to&#xD;
        all perspectives; impacts to Logical models will also require updates to the Technical models.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Analyze Impact and Opportunity&lt;/strong>  the (potential) introduction of new technology to the enterprise&#xD;
        may have widespread impacts. These are analyzed to determine if the impact is either just to the Logical&#xD;
        perspective or the Technology perspective (or perhaps no impact at all), or it has an impact at the business level.&#xD;
        Business level impacts require a different approach, not just a simple update to the business models. The impact&#xD;
        may be simplification or alteration of business processes, or it may require or provide the opportunity for a new&#xD;
        approach, or even a new business line or division (i.e., a new product or service). The impact level and&#xD;
        opportunity is defined and agreed.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Update Business Models&lt;/strong>  the business perspective is updated as required by the business change or&#xD;
        issue resolution.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Update Logical Models&lt;/strong>  the logical perspective is updated as required by the business change or&#xD;
        issue resolution and the changes to the business model.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Update Technical Models&lt;/strong>  the technical perspective is updated as required by the business change&#xD;
        or issue resolution and the changes to the business and logical models.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Update Migration Plan&lt;/strong>  migration plans are always updated once changes to the architecture are&#xD;
        completed.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    In addition, the updated IT architecture may then be &lt;em>used&lt;/em> within enterprise IT management processes to aid in&#xD;
    planning and migration. See: &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../UAM/deliveryprocesses/uam_it_architecture_in-ent_4608CDE7.html&quot; guid=&quot;_YHA_kafREeS8vLSVufajPQ&quot;>Delivery&#xD;
    Process: UAM in the Enterprise&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <keyConsiderations>If the change is minor enough, as specified by the enteprise's management parameters, then this process will not be&#xD;
necessary, but existing IT architectures will have the minor updates applied. However, if the impact on the IT architecture&#xD;
is substantial then this process is necessary to ensure that the IT architecture remains current and up-to-date.</keyConsiderations>
    <usageGuidance>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The need for maintenance of an IT architecture centers around three separate drivers for change:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        An update to the business (i.e., strategy, plans, products, services, etc.);&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        An update to the technology used, or proposed to be used;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Identification of a problem with the existing architecture or operational system.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Each of these drivers is addressed within the defined delivery process.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    If the change is minor enough, as specified by the enteprise's management parameters, then this process will not be&#xD;
    necessary, but existing IT architectures will have the minor updates applied. However, if the impact on the IT&#xD;
    architecture is substantial then this process is necessary to ensure that the IT architecture remains current and&#xD;
    up-to-date.&#xD;
&lt;/p></usageGuidance>
    <purpose>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_Delivery__Maintain&quot; name=&quot;XE_Delivery__Maintain&quot;>&lt;/a>IT architectures will quickly become dated if not&#xD;
maintained. They should be viewed as an asset and kept up-to-date.</purpose>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription>
