  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription xmi:id="-kZykgPHbTeyPdcLprsBjow" name="uam_update_migration_plan,_bEZvkEQtEeShYIpiBstbOQ" guid="-kZykgPHbTeyPdcLprsBjow">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    To develop a migration plan the current environment is compared with a target architecture (a gap analysis is done) and&#xD;
    the differences noted. Knowledge of dependencies between components, technologies, processes and systems, among other&#xD;
    aspects, is then used to order these steps into a logical sequence of activities, with the end result being the&#xD;
    enterprise's environment ending up in the target state as defined by the target enterprise architecture.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    In the case of an update, the gap analysis may be a comparison of the old target architecture with the new target&#xD;
    architecture. This will simplify the analysis and speed up the update process, but only if the update was not&#xD;
    substantial.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Once the migration plan is updated, it is then up to the organization, through its management and planning processes,&#xD;
    to execute based upon this plan. Each enterprise has its own governance processes; for the business and for the&#xD;
    associated IT systems. A separate generic governance process has been defined within UAM that specifies where and how&#xD;
    to integrate UAM within these pre-existing enterprise management&amp;nbsp;processes. This &quot;Delivery Process&quot; is to be&#xD;
    adapted and integrated into the enteprise's processes. See:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../UAM/deliveryprocesses/uam_it_architecture_in-ent_4608CDE7.html&quot; guid=&quot;_YHA_kafREeS8vLSVufajPQ&quot;>Delivery&#xD;
    Process: UAM in the Enterprise&lt;/a>&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>Migration planning is done to define the steps (normally a series of projects) necessary to move the enterprise's&#xD;
information technology environment from an existing state to a target state as defined by a target architecture. This&#xD;
update is done as a results of an update to the IT architecture. Adjustments are made as needed to accommodate the changes.</usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription xmi:id="-SzL6_RVjxeuNHXkZZTBthg" name="uam_approve_migration,_ztGpYKijEeS8vLSVufajPQ" guid="-SzL6_RVjxeuNHXkZZTBthg">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Having an understanding of the gaps between&amp;nbsp;the old target IT architecture and the new&amp;nbsp;target architecture is&#xD;
    the starting point for the update to the migration plan. This information is provided from doing a&amp;nbsp;&lt;a&#xD;
    class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/tasks/uam_gap_analysis_37973A91.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_PogDkNKaEdyTfZVjf0InKw&quot;>Task: Target vs. Existing Gap Analysis&lt;/a>, but with the &quot;target&quot; being the updated&#xD;
    target architecture and the &quot;existing&quot; IT architecture being the old target architecture. The next step&amp;nbsp;is to&#xD;
    understand the gaps and how they affect the existing migration plan.&amp;nbsp;The new migration plan must address technical&#xD;
    considerations, but must also include business considerations such as their needs for new or modified capabilities and&#xD;
    cost/benefit considerations.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>&lt;p>&#xD;
    An updated migration plan needs to be reviewed by management and approved. Once approved the next steps&#xD;
    (outlined/suggested in the Review Record) are typically actioned through the normal enterprise IT management processes,&#xD;
    generically outlined in: &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../UAM/deliveryprocesses/uam_it_architecture_in-ent_4608CDE7.html&quot; guid=&quot;_YHA_kafREeS8vLSVufajPQ&quot;>Delivery&#xD;
    Process: UAM in the Enterprise&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The approval of a Migration Plan will typically involve managers, both operations and technical, from the areas&#xD;
    involved in the migration.&#xD;
&lt;/p></usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription>
