  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-B9yjl4Z9QMOHvvXyrNqmzw" name="ea_assess_simple,_fdlAEdpUEdyp3veHciZnuA" guid="-B9yjl4Z9QMOHvvXyrNqmzw">
    <usageGuidance>The decision made here is to iterate again or not. If not, then a final more formal architecture review is undertaken: a&#xD;
more inclusive &lt;em>peer review&lt;/em>.</usageGuidance>
    <refinedDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The newly created architecture is assessed from these and other perspectives:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To check it for completeness;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To check it for consistency in everything from naming conventions to concepts and structure;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To detect any architectural design flaws. Architectural flaws are known to be the hardest to fix and&amp;nbsp;the most&#xD;
        damaging in the long run;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To detect a potential mismatch between the requirements and the architecture: over-design, unrealistic&#xD;
        requirements, or missing requirements. In particular the assessment may examine some aspects often neglected in the&#xD;
        areas of operation, administration and maintenance;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To evaluate one or more specific architectural qualities: performance, reliability, modifiability, security,&#xD;
        safety;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To identify reuse opportunities;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Ensure conformance with enterprise and business domain standards.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    If the IT architecture is deemed acceptable and complete, then it moves on the the final step: a &lt;em>stakeholder&#xD;
    review&lt;/em>. If more work is needed then another development iteration is executed.&#xD;
&lt;/p></refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
