  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-wXWx-FlPKTZIvm17KM4fGQ" name="ea_define_business_entity,_5TexQN7tEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="-wXWx-FlPKTZIvm17KM4fGQ">
    <keyConsiderations>The business entities identified during this task are high-level, but their definition must be very precise, and agreed by&#xD;
stakeholders. The identification and definition of attributes is optional.</keyConsiderations>
    <usageGuidance>At the Business level the important focus is on identification and definition of the entities. Key and important attributes&#xD;
are defined, but the identification of attributes is optional. Relationships are also important since they support the&#xD;
business and defined business processes.</usageGuidance>
    <refinedDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    This task finds and defines the business entities involved in the architecture in question. Related, and very&#xD;
    important, is the definition of standard vocabulary that is used to describe and discuss the business.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    To find candidate business entities, consider what information each business activity and actor&amp;nbsp;works with. The&#xD;
    information that must be queried, validated, created, or communicated is a good starting point. Only significant,&#xD;
    persistent information should be considered as a business entity.&#xD;
&lt;/p></refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-hzW3EAVlZdkIVfzghjwZVg" name="ea_define_business_process,_TlgTkN7uEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="-hzW3EAVlZdkIVfzghjwZVg">
    <keyConsiderations>The business processes identified during this task are high-level, but their definition must be precise, and agreed by&#xD;
stakeholders.</keyConsiderations>
    <usageGuidance>&lt;p>&#xD;
    At the Business level the main focus is typically on this process model. It is what the main (business) stakeholders&#xD;
    are familiar with, and it is the key aspect for the IT architecture. Related to processes and activities are the&#xD;
    entities consumed and produced, along with the actors involved. Note that only Actors are defined at the Business&#xD;
    level; roles are defined at the Logical level. Logical level roles, after this perspective is defined, may be rolled&#xD;
    back up into the Business level models in order to to complete the descriptions at this level for the business&#xD;
    stakeholders.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Optionally business rules and business events are defined. These will be fully defined at the Logical and Technical&#xD;
    levels. Therefore, only important rules and events are defined at the Business level.&#xD;
&lt;/p></usageGuidance>
    <refinedDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;span&#xD;
    style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Times New Roman','serif'; mso-fareast-font-family: 'Times New Roman'; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-ansi-language: EN-CA; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA&quot;>&lt;font&#xD;
     face=&quot;Arial&quot;>This task defines, at the business level, the business&amp;nbsp;processes involved in the architecture in&#xD;
    question. Also, and very important, is the definition of standard business vocabulary that is used to describe and&#xD;
    discuss the business activities and processes.&lt;/font>&lt;/span>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;span&#xD;
    style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Times New Roman','serif'; mso-fareast-font-family: 'Times New Roman'; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-ansi-language: EN-CA; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA&quot;>&lt;font&#xD;
     face=&quot;Arial&quot;>To find candidate business processes examine business descriptions and other sources of business process&#xD;
    information.&lt;/font>&lt;/span>&#xD;
&lt;/p></refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-R3HxhrQX1ZMSGY6MonEGbw" name="ea_define_business_locations,_YrLz8N7uEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="-R3HxhrQX1ZMSGY6MonEGbw">
    <keyConsiderations>The locations identified during this task are a preliminary view, but their definition must be precise enough to permit&#xD;
further analysis, and agreed by stakeholders.</keyConsiderations>
    <usageGuidance>At the Business level the main focus is typically on the process model, but the locations model is also important,&#xD;
especially if the system spans multiple conceptual or physical locations. This model is usually very simple at the Business&#xD;
level, with the important modeling done at the Logical and Technical level. The most important definition at the Business&#xD;
level is that of the Domain within which the system is located. Included within the Domain definition is the specification&#xD;
of the &lt;em>authority&lt;/em>; the person or office that defines the rules and policies that govern the usage of entities and&#xD;
services within the Domain.</usageGuidance>
    <refinedDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;span>&lt;font face=&quot;Arial&quot;>This task finds and defines the business locations where the &quot;system&quot; being architected&#xD;
    operates along with relationships between these locations. Also, and very important, is the definition of standard&#xD;
    business vocabulary that is used to describe and discuss the business.&lt;/font>&lt;/span>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;span>&lt;font face=&quot;Arial&quot;>To find locations,&amp;nbsp;look at business&amp;nbsp;workflows and&amp;nbsp;business actors involved.&#xD;
    Stakeholders are a good source for this information.&lt;/font>&lt;/span>&#xD;
&lt;/p></refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-9NjDJgqiU5QTzQXHbpPcJg" name="ea_define_business_roles,_hx4Ssd7uEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="-9NjDJgqiU5QTzQXHbpPcJg">
    <keyConsiderations>The Business Actors identified during this task are high-level, but their definition must be very precise, and agreed by&#xD;
stakeholders.</keyConsiderations>
    <usageGuidance>At the Business level the main focus is typically on the process model. It is what the main (business) stakeholders are&#xD;
familiar with, and it is the key aspect for the IT architecture. Related to processes and activities are the entities&#xD;
consumed and produced, along with the &lt;em>actors&lt;/em> involved. Note that only Actors are defined at the Business level;&#xD;
roles are defined at the Logical level. Logical level roles, after this perspective is defined, may be rolled back up into&#xD;
the Business level models in order to to complete the descriptions at this level for the business stakeholders. Therefore,&#xD;
the Business Roles Model is typically very simple, unless the system being architected is large.</usageGuidance>
    <refinedDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    This task finds and defines the Business Actors interacting with the system. Also, and very important, is the&#xD;
    definition of standard business vocabulary that is used to describe and discuss the business.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    To find candidate Business Actors, examine the processes involved. At the Business level we only concern ourselves with&#xD;
    Actors, external actors, that interact with the system. Roles are not defined at this level since their definition has&#xD;
    implications: the activity is Manual or involves a User (i.e. the activity cannot be automated).&#xD;
&lt;/p></refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-yj9QHVRXRag0PcbA4Cmd7Q" name="ea_assess_business_model,_8AyPkd7uEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="-yj9QHVRXRag0PcbA4Cmd7Q">
    <usageGuidance>The decision made here is to iterate again or not. If not, then a final more formal architecture review is undertaken: a&#xD;
more inclusive &lt;em>peer review&lt;/em>.</usageGuidance>
    <refinedDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The newly created architecture is assessed from these and other perspectives:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To check it for completeness;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To check it for consistency in everything from naming conventions to concepts and structure;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To detect any architectural design flaws. Architectural flaws are known to be the hardest to fix and&amp;nbsp;the most&#xD;
        damaging in the long run;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To detect a potential mismatch between the requirements and the architecture: over-design, unrealistic&#xD;
        requirements, or missing requirements. In particular the assessment may examine some aspects often neglected in the&#xD;
        areas of operation, administration and maintenance;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To evaluate one or more specific architectural qualities: performance, reliability, modifiability, security,&#xD;
        safety;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To identify reuse opportunities;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Ensure conformance with enterprise and business domain standards.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    If the IT architecture is deemed acceptable and complete, then it moves on the the final step: a &lt;em>stakeholder&#xD;
    review&lt;/em>. If more work is needed then another development iteration is executed.&#xD;
&lt;/p></refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-ciPSU5pphBciSiloXhGfWg" name="ea_ccv_system,_J8dvMd8OEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="-ciPSU5pphBciSiloXhGfWg">
    <usageGuidance>Capturing a common vocabulary used in the architecture definitions is extremely important when developing&#xD;
IT&amp;nbsp;architectures. This helps in developing the common understanding and agreed and more precise terminology to be used&#xD;
in describing the business and the more technical views of the business. The Architecture Glossary for the project is&#xD;
augmented as required during the work on the Logical Perspective.</usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-W-9lyFf2e2Z2nQ_QwNd2ZQ" name="ea_ccv_tech,_AuE2kN8aEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="-W-9lyFf2e2Z2nQ_QwNd2ZQ">
    <usageGuidance>Capturing a common vocabulary used in the architecture definitions is extremely important when developing&#xD;
IT&amp;nbsp;architectures. This helps in developing the common understanding and agreed and more precise terminology to be used&#xD;
in describing the business and the more technical views of the business. The Architecture Glossary for the project is&#xD;
augmented as required during the work on the Technical Perspective.</usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-cCLqtnpK4qKMVmN7-p41Ew" name="ea_define_logical_entity,_fWoKsN8OEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="-cCLqtnpK4qKMVmN7-p41Ew">
    <usageGuidance>At the Logical level the entity model can and should get more detailed, but stay logical.&amp;nbsp;All attributes are defined,&#xD;
but the identification of structural attributes (i.e., keys, etc.) is optional. Relationships are very important, since&#xD;
they support the business and business processes, and should be well-defined in this model. Persistence aspects may also be&#xD;
included in the model.</usageGuidance>
    <refinedDescription>Logical entities are the things passed between activities or produced by activities and tasks (see: &lt;a&#xD;
class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/guidances/whitepapers/uam_bpmn_intro_tutorial_426154F6.html&quot;&#xD;
guid=&quot;_gYTbgN2MEdyVUKFKTmaZUA&quot;>Whitepaper: BPMN - an Introductory Tutorial&lt;/a>). They are likely persistent, but not&#xD;
necessarily. It is important to document enough detail&amp;nbsp;of these entities at this stage of the architecture to&#xD;
understand how they are used within business processes, and what relationships between them are required, all in the&#xD;
support of the business processes and activities. Refinement of their definitions and structure is also done.</refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-bar5qGrhWhmou4QA-n_ycg" name="ea_define_logical_process,_oxnecd8OEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="-bar5qGrhWhmou4QA-n_ycg">
    <usageGuidance>&lt;p>&#xD;
    At the Logical level the focus is on all aspects, but the Process Model is still at the heart of the architecture. The&#xD;
    business stakeholders are familiar with this aspect, and it is the most important aspect for the IT architecture.&#xD;
    Related to processes and activities are the entities consumed and produced, along with the actors/roles involved. Roles&#xD;
    are now defined at the Logical level, and aid in understanding how actors/roles relate to the defined activities. This&#xD;
    is fully flushed out in the Logical Roles Model.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    All logical business rules and logical business events are defined, completing this model.&#xD;
&lt;/p></usageGuidance>
    <refinedDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    This task defines, at the logical level, the processes involved in the architecture in question. Also, and very&#xD;
    important, is the definition of standard business vocabulary that is used to describe and discuss the business and the&#xD;
    solution. Also added at the logical level are the roles associated with the activities and tasks that define the&#xD;
    processes.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The Business Process Model is used along with input from stakeholders to define and refine the Logical Process Model.&#xD;
&lt;/p></refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="--FSHRRdL103ye3765Dgh6w" name="ea_define_logical_location,_tFZn0d8OEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="--FSHRRdL103ye3765Dgh6w">
    <usageGuidance>At the Logical level the locations model is important, especially if the system spans multiple logical or physical&#xD;
locations. This model is usually very simple at the Business level, with the important modeling done at the Logical and&#xD;
Technical level. The Logical level locations model defines the distribution of activities and services across locations.&#xD;
Locations details are added in support of IT security and include the clear definition of Zones and the elements contained&#xD;
within these Zones. Zone boundaries, if any, are generically outlined. IP network elements are also defined; a logical&#xD;
level model of the supporting network.</usageGuidance>
    <refinedDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    This task defines, at the logical level, the locations involved in the IT architecture of the system. As in&#xD;
    real-estate, locations are very important to any business in terms of the processes and tasks (i.e. business services)&#xD;
    that are supported at each type of location. This model directly impacts upon the deployment of systems and services to&#xD;
    the locations, which in turn defines many other factors and requirements, such as cost, network topography and&#xD;
    requirements, deployment of servers, storage and other infrastructure services, among many others.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The Business&amp;nbsp;Locations Model is used, along with input from stakeholders, to define and refine the Logical&#xD;
    Locations Model.&#xD;
&lt;/p></refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-C2EXuyn_gCbamfTnuraH9w" name="ea_define_logical_role,_0lzeMN8OEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="-C2EXuyn_gCbamfTnuraH9w">
    <usageGuidance>The Logical level is where the &quot;automate vs. user&quot; decisions are made. In other words, is an activity a fully automated&#xD;
service or is there user interaction. Once this decision is made the definition of the roles that interact with the&#xD;
activities are defined. These roles are also related to the actors involved, and in turn the users&amp;nbsp;related to these&#xD;
actors.&amp;nbsp;Also, processes and activities are where entities are consumed and produced, and thus completing the&#xD;
(indirect) relationship between entities and the actors/roles involved. See: &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
href=&quot;./../../UAM/guidances/guidelines/uam_user-actor-role_8210ACA7.html&quot; guid=&quot;_r8jW8OPQEdy7f9KmjDtwsA&quot;>Guideline: Users,&#xD;
Actors and Roles&lt;/a></usageGuidance>
    <refinedDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;span&#xD;
    style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Times New Roman','serif'; mso-fareast-font-family: 'Times New Roman'; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-ansi-language: EN-CA; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA&quot;>&lt;font&#xD;
     face=&quot;Arial&quot;>This task defines, at the logical level, the actors and roles involved in the architecture in question.&#xD;
    Roles (and associated actors) are very important to any business in terms of the business activities and processes that&#xD;
    the roles execute. This model directly impacts upon the structure of the systems, tasks and processes with which the&#xD;
    roles interact. Actors interact with the system through roles, therefore these relationships are also explored and&#xD;
    defined.&lt;/font>&lt;/span>&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;span&#xD;
    style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Times New Roman','serif'; mso-fareast-font-family: 'Times New Roman'; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-ansi-language: EN-CA; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA&quot;>&lt;font&#xD;
     face=&quot;Arial&quot;>The Business&amp;nbsp;Roles Model and Logical Process Model are used, along with input from stakeholders, to&#xD;
    define and refine the Logical Roles Model.&lt;/font>&lt;/span>&#xD;
&lt;/p></refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-ktcSgwzcJx9wTAyYysZm2Q" name="ea_assess_system_model,_XI5e0d8PEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="-ktcSgwzcJx9wTAyYysZm2Q">
    <usageGuidance>The decision made here is to iterate again or not. If not, then a final more formal architecture review is undertaken: a&#xD;
more inclusive &lt;em>peer review&lt;/em>.</usageGuidance>
    <refinedDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The newly created architecture is assessed from these and other perspectives:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To check it for completeness;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To check it for consistency in everything from naming conventions to concepts and structure;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To detect any architectural design flaws. Architectural flaws are known to be the hardest to fix and&amp;nbsp;the most&#xD;
        damaging in the long run;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To detect a potential mismatch between the requirements and the architecture: over-design, unrealistic&#xD;
        requirements, or missing requirements. In particular the assessment may examine some aspects often neglected in the&#xD;
        areas of operation, administration and maintenance;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To evaluate one or more specific architectural qualities: performance, reliability, modifiability, security,&#xD;
        safety;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To identify reuse opportunities;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Ensure conformance with enterprise and business domain standards.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    If the IT architecture is deemed acceptable and complete, then it moves on the the final step: a &lt;em>stakeholder&#xD;
    review&lt;/em>. If more work is needed then another development iteration is executed.&#xD;
&lt;/p></refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-R34vS4iekW3Kg7ckuIrxgA" name="ea_define_tech_entity,_LUvTQd8aEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="-R34vS4iekW3Kg7ckuIrxgA">
    <usageGuidance>At the Technical level the entity model can get as detailed as desired, and as dictated by the context and&#xD;
objectives.&amp;nbsp;All attributes are defined, including the identification of structural attributes (i.e., keys, etc.) if&#xD;
desired. Relationships are very important, since they support the business and business processes, and should be&#xD;
well-defined in this model. Persistence aspects may also be included in the model.</usageGuidance>
    <refinedDescription>Technical entities are the things passed between activities or produced by activities and tasks (see: &lt;a&#xD;
class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/guidances/whitepapers/uam_bpmn_intro_tutorial_426154F6.html&quot;&#xD;
guid=&quot;_gYTbgN2MEdyVUKFKTmaZUA&quot;>Whitepaper: BPMN - an Introductory Tutorial&lt;/a>). They are likely persistent, but not&#xD;
necessarily. It is important to document enough detail&amp;nbsp;of these entities at this stage of the architecture to&#xD;
understand how the technologies chosen will support their use within processes, and what relationships between them are&#xD;
required, which also influences technology choices. Refinement of their definitions and structure is also done, again in&#xD;
support of technology choices and required refinements of this and other models within the architecture.</refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-8snDRBl5lZRtfAt_Ul3D6A" name="ea_define_tech_process,_Q-H9oN8aEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="-8snDRBl5lZRtfAt_Ul3D6A">
    <usageGuidance>&lt;p>&#xD;
    At the Technical level the focus is on all aspects, but the Process Model is still at the heart of the architecture.&#xD;
    The business stakeholders are familiar with this aspect, and it is the most important aspect for the IT architecture&#xD;
    since it has great influence on the other aspects. Related to processes and activities are the entities consumed and&#xD;
    produced, along with the actors/roles involved. Roles defined at the Logical level are refined, and aid in&#xD;
    understanding how actors/roles relate to the defined activities. This access and usage of activities/entities is fully&#xD;
    flushed out in the Technical Roles Model.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    All technical level business rules and business events are defined, completing this model.&#xD;
&lt;/p></usageGuidance>
    <refinedDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;span&#xD;
    style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Times New Roman','serif'; mso-fareast-font-family: 'Times New Roman'; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-ansi-language: EN-CA; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA&quot;>&lt;font&#xD;
     face=&quot;Arial&quot;>This task defines, at the technical level, the business&amp;nbsp;processes and tasks involved in the&#xD;
    architecture in question. Also, and very important, is the definition of standard vocabulary that is used to describe&#xD;
    and discuss the business and the solution.&lt;/font>&lt;/span>&amp;nbsp; Also the roles associated with the activities and tasks&#xD;
    are refined at the technical level with the view to making them usable for Roles Based Access Control (RBAC).&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;span&#xD;
    style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Times New Roman','serif'; mso-fareast-font-family: 'Times New Roman'; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-ansi-language: EN-CA; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA&quot;>&lt;font&#xD;
     face=&quot;Arial&quot;>The Logical Process Model is used along with input from stakeholders and experts&amp;nbsp;to define and&#xD;
    refine the Technical Process Model.&lt;/font>&lt;/span>&#xD;
&lt;/p></refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-LeCZB1WXwjScuQkyywX4oA" name="ea_define_tech_locations,_XhLa8d8aEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="-LeCZB1WXwjScuQkyywX4oA">
    <usageGuidance>At the Technical level the locations model is very important. This model is usually very simple at the Business level, with&#xD;
the important modeling done at the Logical and Technical level. The Technical level locations model defines the&#xD;
distribution of activities and services across locations, and how they are interconnected through communications link. The&#xD;
technology used to support this distribution is specified in detail. Locations details are added in support of IT security&#xD;
and include the clear definition of Zones and the elements contained within these Zones. Zone boundaries, if any, are&#xD;
detailed.&amp;nbsp;IP network elements are also specified; a technical level model of the supporting network.</usageGuidance>
    <refinedDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    This task defines, at the technical level, the locations involved in the architecture in question. As in real-estate,&#xD;
    locations are very important to any business in terms of the business processes and tasks that are supported at each&#xD;
    type of location. This model defines the deployment of hardware and software systems and services to the locations,&#xD;
    which in turn defines many other factors and requirements, such as cost, network topography and bandwidths, deployment&#xD;
    of servers, storage and other infrastructure services, among many others.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The Logical Locations Model is used, along with input from stakeholders and IT experts, to define and refine the&#xD;
    Technical Locations Model.&#xD;
&lt;/p></refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-QOIgoG0vKQMYRS_ob8pRvg" name="uam_define_tech_roles,_d1SdUN8aEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="-QOIgoG0vKQMYRS_ob8pRvg">
    <usageGuidance>The Technical level is where the&amp;nbsp;final decisions are made regarding IT security (RBAC), Actor and Role&#xD;
structures,&amp;nbsp;and process interface design. Roles are related to the actors involved, and in turn the users&amp;nbsp;related&#xD;
to these actors and through this analysis the optimal structures are defined.&amp;nbsp;Also, processes and activities are where&#xD;
entities are consumed and produced, and thus completing the (indirect) relationship between entities and the actors/roles&#xD;
involved. See: &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/guidances/guidelines/uam_user-actor-role_8210ACA7.html&quot;&#xD;
guid=&quot;_r8jW8OPQEdy7f9KmjDtwsA&quot;>Guideline: Users, Actors and Roles&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;and &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
href=&quot;./../../UAM/guidances/guidelines/uam_rbac_E500D24E.html&quot; guid=&quot;_Y8UWoKNBEeScBuKTf-rcGA&quot;>Guideline: Role-Based Access&#xD;
Control&lt;/a>.</usageGuidance>
    <refinedDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;span&#xD;
    style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Times New Roman','serif'; mso-fareast-font-family: 'Times New Roman'; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-ansi-language: EN-CA; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA&quot;>&lt;font&#xD;
     face=&quot;Arial&quot;>This task defines, at the technical level, the actors and roles involved in the architecture in question.&#xD;
    Roles (and associated actors) are very important to any business in terms of the activities and processes that the&#xD;
    roles execute. This model directly impacts upon the technologies chosen to support the interactions that these roles&#xD;
    have with the defined tasks and processes.&lt;/font>&lt;/span>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;span&#xD;
    style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Times New Roman','serif'; mso-fareast-font-family: 'Times New Roman'; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-ansi-language: EN-CA; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA&quot;>&lt;font&#xD;
     face=&quot;Arial&quot;>The Logical Roles Model and Technical Process Model are used, along with input from stakeholders, to&#xD;
    define and refine the Technical Roles Model.&lt;/font>&lt;/span>&#xD;
&lt;/p></refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-YLEFvBA35KixCUPScVwCvQ" name="uam_assess_tech_models,_wGu0Yd8aEdynr9jlfK-aMA" guid="-YLEFvBA35KixCUPScVwCvQ">
    <usageGuidance>The decision made here is to iterate again or not. If not, then a final more formal architecture review is undertaken: a&#xD;
more inclusive &lt;em>peer review&lt;/em>.</usageGuidance>
    <refinedDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The newly created architecture is assessed from these and other perspectives:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To check it for completeness;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To check it for consistency in everything from naming conventions to concepts and structure;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To detect any architectural design flaws. Architectural flaws are known to be the hardest to fix and&amp;nbsp;the most&#xD;
        damaging in the long run;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To detect a potential mismatch between the requirements and the architecture: over-design, unrealistic&#xD;
        requirements, or missing requirements. In particular the assessment may examine some aspects often neglected in the&#xD;
        areas of operation, administration and maintenance;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To evaluate one or more specific architectural qualities: performance, reliability, modifiability, security,&#xD;
        safety;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To identify reuse opportunities;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Ensure conformance with enterprise and business domain standards.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    If the IT architecture is deemed acceptable and complete, then it moves on the the final step: a &lt;em>stakeholder&#xD;
    review&lt;/em>. If more work is needed then another development iteration is executed.&#xD;
&lt;/p></refinedDescription>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription xmi:id="-enwEygZW-URkmL4oORIUAQ" name="uam_define_tech_impact,_Ls_6AUQoEeShYIpiBstbOQ" guid="-enwEygZW-URkmL4oORIUAQ">
    <usageGuidance>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The application of new technologies with existing architectures, and systems, can be quite complex. The only simple&#xD;
    scenario here is if there is a &quot;green field&quot;; if no existing system exists. This analysis must still be undertaken,&#xD;
    however. This ensure that any interactions of this new system with existing systems are understood. A much simpler&#xD;
    analysis.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Ensure that the new technology is clearly understood, since sometimes the interactions or affects on the architecture&#xD;
    are more complicated and profound that thought initially. Understand the details of the new technology (perhaps with&#xD;
    the help of outside IT experts) and do&amp;nbsp;a thorough analysis. Impacts may also be obscure; look at the system from&#xD;
    multiple perspectives, and perhaps do a walk-through of the process(s) if necessary.&#xD;
&lt;/p></usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription xmi:id="-vkwC0Recp_AEuNOCtBWXPw" name="uam_analyse_models,_DOTW8ERKEeShYIpiBstbOQ" guid="-vkwC0Recp_AEuNOCtBWXPw">
    <keyConsiderations>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The architectural analysis done involves the identification of issues, opportunities, and the way forward. Ensuring&#xD;
    that the architecture addresses the enterprise IT strategy and direction and supports the enterprise's business&#xD;
    strategy and direction has been completed. Now the IT architecture is&amp;nbsp;looked at from other perspectives in order&#xD;
    to discover possible issues with its structure, technology, or even skill-sets required to implement, operate and&#xD;
    maintain the proposed system.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h5>&#xD;
    Aspects analyzed, as a minimum:&#xD;
&lt;/h5>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Structure and flexibility; of processes, locations,&amp;nbsp;and other aspects;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Technologies and the organization's skills sets with respect to these technologies;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Operations aspects of the new IT architecture;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Maintenance aspects of the new architecture&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        End-to-end integration and usability, from a user perspective;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Non-functional aspects and how they are dealt with, now and in the longer term;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Migration feasibility, costs, and issues.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></keyConsiderations>
    <usageGuidance>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The architectural analysis done involves the identification of issues, opportunities, and the way forward. Ensuring&#xD;
    that the architecture addresses the enterprise IT strategy and direction and supports the enterprise's business&#xD;
    strategy and direction has been completed. Now the IT architecture is&amp;nbsp;looked at from other perspectives in order&#xD;
    to discover possible issues with its structure, technology, or even skill-sets required to implement, operate and&#xD;
    maintain the proposed system.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h5>&#xD;
    Aspects analyzed, as a minimum:&#xD;
&lt;/h5>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Structure and flexibility; of processes, locations,&amp;nbsp;and other aspects;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Technologies and the organization's skills sets with respect to these technologies;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Operations aspects of the new IT architecture;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Maintenance aspects of the new architecture&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        End-to-end integration and usability, from a user perspective;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Non-functional aspects and how they are dealt with, now and in the longer term;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Migration feasibility, costs, and issues.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription xmi:id="-5EVFxyl0mQGGQLUQFVH2lQ" name="uam_develop_training,_N-XnQURKEeShYIpiBstbOQ" guid="-5EVFxyl0mQGGQLUQFVH2lQ">
    <usageGuidance>&lt;p>&#xD;
    IT architectures provide the information necessary&amp;nbsp;to develop&amp;nbsp;a number of types of training. Everything from&#xD;
    an overview of the enterprise for new employees (from EA level architectures), to detailed operations guides for users.&#xD;
&lt;/p></usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription xmi:id="-htWBxz_XhxoAuLvuSY7GCQ" name="uam_approve_course,_XSF-gKZ4EeS1o4_8kucAIw" guid="-htWBxz_XhxoAuLvuSY7GCQ">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The &quot;owner&quot; of the course, or perhaps a&amp;nbsp;training unit within the organization, is where the approval rests. IT&#xD;
    architects help in defining the course, and others will finalize its definition, but the &quot;owner&quot; must approve it.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Training is an important part of implementing a system and keeping it running. IT architecture definitions are an&#xD;
    excellent source of information for developing the required training, be it at the user level or even for developers&#xD;
    and maintainers.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>The training course may be developed for and focused on any number of levels and aspects of the IT architecture. Therefore,&#xD;
getting the right people in the room to both develop and approve the course is important, and is obviously based upon the&#xD;
focus of the training.</usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription xmi:id="-eriD2gnlYG-xMeG3rPsDDQ" name="uam_consult,_RhK_oURKEeShYIpiBstbOQ" guid="-eriD2gnlYG-xMeG3rPsDDQ">
    <keyConsiderations>The objectives of the consultation should be made very clear prior to meeting with stakeholders. Their expectations must be&#xD;
clear.</keyConsiderations>
    <usageGuidance>The objectives of the consultation should be made very clear prior to meeting with stakeholders. Their expectations must be&#xD;
clear.</usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription xmi:id="-uQh6miCXBrHeFc5Hq5Nx2w" name="uam_consult_next,_ExItAKfyEeS8vLSVufajPQ" guid="-uQh6miCXBrHeFc5Hq5Nx2w">
    <mainDescription>The consultation may focus on many aspects of the IT architecture, from structure of process, to non-functional aspects and&#xD;
the flexibility of the architecture, to the</mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The results of the consultation needs to be reviewed by management and approved. Once approved the next steps&#xD;
    (outlined/suggested in the Review Record) are typically actioned through the normal enterprise IT management processes,&#xD;
    generically outlined in: &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../UAM/deliveryprocesses/uam_it_architecture_in-ent_4608CDE7.html&quot; guid=&quot;_YHA_kafREeS8vLSVufajPQ&quot;>Delivery&#xD;
    Process: UAM in the Enterprise&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The approval of a the results of the consultation will typically involve managers, both operations and technical, from&#xD;
    the areas involved in the architected system.&#xD;
&lt;/p></usageGuidance>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:BreakdownElementDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription xmi:id="-cNH4l_-Xkms8fD6P5DGrCw" name="uam_use_arch,_VTaFkENiEeShYIpiBstbOQ" guid="-cNH4l_-Xkms8fD6P5DGrCw">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The four possible way of &lt;em>using&lt;/em> an IT architecture are:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Analyze Models&lt;/strong> - analysis is used to refine and optimize the models, refine the business and its&#xD;
        processes, agree and refine the proposed logical or technical solutions, and to aid in defining short and long term&#xD;
        strategies (both business and technical);&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Define a Migration Plan&lt;/strong> - the plan that takes the enterprise from an existing IT environment to&#xD;
        the defined target architecture;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Develop Training&lt;/strong> - the creation of a training course based upon the defined IT architecture&#xD;
        documentation for a system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Consultation&lt;/strong> - aim of consultation is two-fold: to provide feedback to stakeholders on the defined&#xD;
        architecture, and to solicit input from them on the IT architecture.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Each of these uses is addressed within the defined delivery process. In addition, the IT architecture may then be&#xD;
    &lt;em>used&lt;/em> within enterprise IT management processes to aid in planning and migration. See: &lt;a&#xD;
    class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../UAM/deliveryprocesses/uam_it_architecture_in-ent_4608CDE7.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_YHA_kafREeS8vLSVufajPQ&quot;>Delivery Process: UAM in the Enterprise&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The usage of completed IT architectures depends upon the objectives of the architecture. For example, an architecture&#xD;
    may be defined in order understand and implement a rationalized and more efficient IP network. This objective will then&#xD;
    drive the usage of the IT architecture.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
    <keyConsiderations>The usage of completed IT architectures depends upon the objectives of the architecture. For example, an architecture may&#xD;
be defined in order understand and implement a rationalized and more efficient IP network. This objective will then drive&#xD;
the usage of the IT architecture.</keyConsiderations>
    <usageGuidance>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Using an IT architecture is categorized as follows:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Analyze Models&lt;/strong> - analysis is used to refine and optimize the models, refine the business and its&#xD;
        processes, agree and refine the proposed logical or technical solutions, and to aid in defining short and long term&#xD;
        strategies (both business and technical);&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Define a Migration Plan&lt;/strong> - the plan that takes the enterprise from an existing IT environment to&#xD;
        the defined target architecture;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Develop Training&lt;/strong> - the creation of a training course based upon the defined IT architecture&#xD;
        documentation for a system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Consultation&lt;/strong> - aim of consultation is two-fold: to provide feedback to stakeholders on the defined&#xD;
        architecture, and to solicit input from them on the IT architecture.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Each of these uses is addressed within the defined delivery process.&#xD;
&lt;/p></usageGuidance>
    <purpose>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_Delivery__Use_Architecture&quot; name=&quot;XE_Delivery__Use_Architecture&quot;>&lt;/a>IT architectures are developed for a&#xD;
purpose; generally to advance the interests of the enterprise through the definition and improvement of the supporting IT&#xD;
systems. These activities directly support these objectives.</purpose>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription xmi:id="-I6bUoQ2uWipT025dYpSSqg" name="uam_manage_ads,_fZGhcK5FEeSje88TfZnHOQ" guid="-I6bUoQ2uWipT025dYpSSqg">
    <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;span lang=&quot;EN-US&quot;>This phase has the following goals:&lt;/span>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Create an Architecture Decision (AD): &#xD;
        &lt;ul>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Define the context of the problem, issue or decision;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Define the constraints, imposed by existing architecture, enterprise standards or others;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Define the rationale for the decision, through a well researched summary of the facts;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Extract the implications of the AD, on current systems, future systems, support aspects and other aspects;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Define or refine the specifics of the decision;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
        &lt;/ul>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Get the AD reviewed and approved by the appropriate review body;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Update the Architecture Glossary as required.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></mainDescription>
    <usageGuidance>An architectural decision may be defined at any time during the development of an architecture, a project, during business&#xD;
planning and in many other situations. This is an on-going activity.</usageGuidance>
    <purpose>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_Delivery__Architectural_Decision&quot; name=&quot;XE_Delivery__Architectural_Decision&quot;>&lt;/a>The purpose of this activity is&#xD;
to define an Architectural Decision and get it approved and published. Documenting important decisions provides a&#xD;
repository (of decisions) that will help guide other architects, managers, and implementers in being compliant with&#xD;
enterprise and business domain standards. They also provide a source of information for re-visiting decisions over time.</purpose>
    <howtoStaff>&lt;span&#xD;
style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Times New Roman','serif'; mso-ansi-language: EN-CA; mso-fareast-font-family: 'Times New Roman'; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA&quot;>&lt;font&#xD;
 face=&quot;Arial&quot;>This activity is best carried out by an individual or a small team (playing the role of Architect), and&#xD;
usually guided by one or two individuals who have deep experience in architecting systems in the relevant domain. It is&#xD;
composed or staffed&amp;nbsp;with cross-functional team members. Issues that are typically architecturally important include&#xD;
structure, technology, performance, scaling, distribution, or other specialty engineering requirements. Significant&#xD;
architectural constraints might also flow from physical and environmental requirements.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font>&lt;/span></howtoStaff>
  </org.eclipse.epf.uma:ActivityDescription>
  <org.eclipse.epf.uma:DescriptorDescription xmi:id="-BqwTjb-5597gs5kymi7IDA" name="uam_define_arch_dec,_4fJY0K5FEeSje88TfZnHOQ" guid="-BqwTjb-5597gs5kymi7IDA">
    <usageGuidance>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The following is provided to aid in deciding if a decision is architecturally significant, or if it is simply a design&#xD;
    decision.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
